{"title_page": "Baba Gana Kingibe", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Baba Gana Kingibe\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office1             = [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]]\n| president1          = [[Umaru Yar'Adua]]\n| term_start1         = July 2007\n| term_end1           = Sept 2008\n| predecessor1        = [[Ufot Ekaette]]\n| successor1          = [[Mahmud Yayale Ahmed]]\n| office2             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]]\n| president2          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start2         = 1997\n| term_end2           = 1998\n| predecessor2        = [[Bashir Dalhatu]]\n| successor2          = Bello Sulaiman\n| office3             = [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]]\n| president3          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start3         = 1995\n| term_end3           = 1997\n| predecessor3        = [[Alex Ibru]]\n| successor3          = [[Bashir Dalhatu]]\n| office4             = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)| Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| president4          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start4         = 1993\n| term_end4           = 1995\n| predecessor4        = [[Matthew Mbu]]\n| successor4          = [[Tom Ikimi]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|6|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Borno State|Borno]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Borno State]], Nigeria)\n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Sussex]]<br>[[Graduate Institute of International Studies]]\n| otherparty          = Peoples Front of Nigeria<br>(1988\u201389)<br>[[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]]<br> (1989\u20131993)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democractic Party]]<br>(1999\u20132015)\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Order of the Niger|GCON]]\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress]]<br>(2015\u2013present)\n| education           = [[Bishop's Stortford College]]\n}}\n'''Baba Gana Kingibe''' [[Order of the Niger|GCON]] (born 25 June 1945) is a Nigerian politician and diplomat who served as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998; and [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]] from 2007 to 2008. In [[1993 Nigerian presidential election]], he was the vice presidential candidate of the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9EAOAQAAMAAJ&q=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&dq=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvjtvYsJLbAhVGsaQKHSBTDewQ6AEIRjAH Profile of Baba Gana Kingibe]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/kingibe-adamu-ali-mustapha-5-others-in-frame-to-succeed-kyari|title=Kingibe, Adamu, Ali, Mustapha, 5 others in frame to succeed Kyari|last1=Omonijo|first1=Bolade|last2=Alli|first2=Yusuf|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=19 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nKingibe was born to the family of Mustafa Shuwa and Ya Kingi Mallam. A [[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] from [[Borno State|Borno]], he grew up in [[Maiduguri]] and attended primary schools there. In 1958, he was admitted into the Borno Provincial Secondary School. In 1960, he left for the [[United Kingdom]] on a government scholarship to complete his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O'Level]] and [[A-level]] at [[Bishop's Stortford College]]. In 1968, he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in [[international relations]] from the [[University of Sussex]] (alongside [[Thabo Mbeki]]), before proceeding to the [[BBC Television]] Training School in London. Kingibe later received a postgraduate diploma from the [[Graduate Institute of International Studies]] in [[Geneva]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2015/07/baba-gana-kingibe-70/|title=Baba Gana Kingibe @ 70|date=2015-07-07|website=Vanguard News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n===Early career===\nIn 1969, he returned to Nigeria and was employed as a [[political science]] [[lecturer]] at the [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]]. At the university, he became acquainted with the [[Kaduna Mafia]], a group of young western-educated [[intellectuals]], [[civil servants]] and [[Nigerian Armed Forces|military officers]] from [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamji.com/haruna/haruna304.htm|title=Ibrahim Tahir: An Appreciation|last=Daura|first=Mamman|date=|website=Gamji|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Towards the end of the [[Nigerian Civil War]], Kingibe the head of the current affairs department at the Broadcasting Corporation of Northern Nigeria (BCNN).<ref name=\"ICIR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.icirnigeria.org/kyari-daura-others-in-buharis-kitchen-cabinet-have-two-things-in-common-journalism-uk-education|title=Kyari, Daura, others in Buhari\u2019s kitchen cabinet have two things in common: journalism, UK education|date=23 September 2019|accessdate=20 April 2020|last=Adebajo|first=Kunle|publisher=International Centre For Investigative Reporting}}</ref>\n\n==Diplomatic service==\nIn 1972, he joined the Nigerian Foreign Service where his first posting was the [[Nigerian High Commission in London]] as a senior political counsellor and later became the head of the political desk.<ref name=ICIR/> \n\nIn 1981, at the age of 36, he was appointed the Nigerian Ambassador to Greece and Cyprus. In 1985, Kingibe was appointed the Nigerian Ambassador to Pakistan by General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blerf.org/index.php/biography/baba-gana-kingibe/|title=BABA, Gana Kingibe|last=Admin|date=2016-11-21|website=Biographical Legacy and Research Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nKingibe also served from October 2002 to September 2006 as the [[Special Envoy]] of the [[African Union]] to [[Sudan]] and subsequently Special Representative of the [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission]] and head of the [[African Union Mission in Sudan]].<ref name=\"GaM22\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nFollowing the [[1976 Nigerian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]], Kingibe was seconded to the [[Supreme Military Council of Nigeria (1966\u20131979)|Supreme Military Headquarters]] (SMHQ) as the Principal Political Secretary, from 1976 to 1979, where he was involved in the planning of the military's transfer of power programme, [[States of Nigeria|states creation]] and [[national delimitation]], [[Local government areas of Nigeria|local government reforms]] and the [[Constitution of Nigeria#1979 constitution (Second Republic)|constitutional drafting committee]] of the [[Second Nigerian Republic]].<ref>African Concord (1990). The New Helmsmen. Concord Press, Ikeja, Lagos. August 13, 1990</ref> In this role, he simultaneously served as the Principal Political Secretary in the [[President of Nigeria|Office of the President]] between 1976 to 1981, serving both General [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] and President [[Shehu Shagari]]. Kingibe later became the [[permanent secretary]] in charge of special services within the [[Cabinet of Nigeria|Cabinet Office]], between 1981 to 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2015/07/baba-gana-kingibe-70/|title=Baba Gana Kingibe @ 70|date=2015-07-07|website=Vanguard News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Party politics===\nKingibe entered party politics in the build up to the transition of the [[Third Nigerian Republic]]. In 1988, he was made director of organization of the People's Front of Nigeria which consisted of politicians such as [[Atiku Abubakar]], [[Bola Tinubu]], [[Abdullahi Aliyu Sumaila]] and [[Rabiu Kwankwaso]], which was then led by [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/04/top-nigeria-politics-forum-liberating-nigeria|title=Top Nigeria politics forum: Liberating Nigeria|last=Sobowale|first=Rasheed|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nThe front later joined with the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]] in 1989. During the conduct of elections for national executive positions in the party, Kingibe was sponsored by the People's Front faction of SDP as the party's chairman, a position he went on to clinch. As party chairman, Kingibe was involved in the organization of party's gubernatorial and presidential primaries in 1991 and 1992 respectively.\n\n=== 1993 presidential election ===\nHowever, after the cancellations of presidential elections in 1992 in which [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua|Shehu Yar'Adua]] was a candidate, Kingibe put himself forward as a presidential candidate. He made a split from his initial camp, the PFN group and used his relationships with SDP state party chairmen to build his campaign. He lost the keenly contested primary conducted in Jos but after much prodding from SDP governors, he was selected by the primary winner, [[MKO Abiola]] as [[Vice-President of Nigeria|Vice-presidential]] running mate, creating a Muslim-Muslim ticket which was initially thought to be a deal breaker in the general elections. The pair won the electoral majority although the result was annulled by abdicating president General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref name=\"Safari Books2\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOVMBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=kingibe++pfn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI7aCfjJ3exgIVAhmSCh3o7gtX#v=onepage&q=kingibe%20%20pfn&f=false/|title=Frank Kokori: The Struggle for June 12|date=2014|publisher=Safari Books|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Abacha administration ===\nKingibe later joined the Abacha administration as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, and [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/335406-why-i-abandoned-june-12-joined-abacha-junta-kingibe.html|title=Why I abandoned June 12, joined Abacha junta - Kingibe - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2019-06-17|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary to the Government===\nIn June 2007, he was appointed [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]].<ref>Idowu Adelusi. Kingibe to move to Aso Rock Villa?. Nigerian Tribune, July 7, 2007.</ref> He was unceremoniously removed from office on September 8, 2008 by the President Umaru Yar'Adua,<ref name=\"GaM2\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref> after spreading rumors about the President's ill-health while believed to be contending for the presidency.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7604889.stm \"Nigerian leader appears in public\"] [[BBC News]]</ref>\n\n=== Buhari administration ===\nKingibe has been a powerful [[\u00c9minence grise|behind the scenes]] decision-maker in the Buhari administration, alongside chief of staff [[Abba Kyari (politician)|Abba Kyari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailycorrespondents.com.ng/2016/08/old-fox-baba-gana-kingibe-nigerias-defacto-prime-minister/|title=Old fox, Baba Gana Kingibe is Nigeria\u2019s defacto Prime Minister|last=Editor|date=2016-08-28|website=Daily Correspondents|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Country\n!Decoration\n!Presenter\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Nigeria]]\n|[[Order of the Niger|Grand Commander of the Order of the Niger]] (GCON); [[File:Ribbon bar of the Order of the Niger.gif|frameless|59x59px]]\n|[[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n|Second highest national honour in Nigeria\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://www.cfr.org/bios/9885/baba_gana_kingibe.html Biography from the Council of Foreign Relations]\n\n{{Foreign Ministers of Nigeria}}{{Interior Ministers of Nigeria}}{{Cabinet of President Umaru Yar'Adua}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingibe, Baba Gana}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Maiduguri]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Nigeria to Greece]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Nigeria to Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Kanuri people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Baba Gana Kingibe\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office1             = [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]]\n| president1          = [[Umaru Yar'Adua]]\n| term_start1         = July 2007\n| term_end1           = Sept 2008\n| predecessor1        = [[Ufot Ekaette]]\n| successor1          = [[Mahmud Yayale Ahmed]]\n| office2             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]]\n| president2          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start2         = 1997\n| term_end2           = 1998\n| predecessor2        = Bashir Dalhatu\n| successor2          = Bello Sulaiman\n| office3             = [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]]\n| president3          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start3         = 1995\n| term_end3           = 1997\n| predecessor3        = [[Alex Ibru]]\n| successor3          = Bashir Dalhatu\n| office4             = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)| Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| president4          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start4         = 1993\n| term_end4           = 1995\n| predecessor4        = [[Matthew Mbu]]\n| successor4          = [[Tom Ikimi]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|6|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Borno State|Borno]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Borno State]], Nigeria)\n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Sussex]]<br>[[Graduate Institute of International Studies]]\n| otherparty          = Peoples Front of Nigeria<br>(1988\u201389)<br>[[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]]<br> (1989\u20131993)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democractic Party]]<br>(1999\u20132015)\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Order of the Niger|GCON]]\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress]]<br>(2015\u2013present)\n| education           = [[Bishop's Stortford College]]\n}}\n'''Baba Gana Kingibe''' [[Order of the Niger|GCON]] (born 25 June 1945) is a Nigerian politician and diplomat who served as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998; and [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]] from 2007 to 2008. In [[1993 Nigerian presidential election]], he was the vice presidential candidate of the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9EAOAQAAMAAJ&q=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&dq=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvjtvYsJLbAhVGsaQKHSBTDewQ6AEIRjAH Profile of Baba Gana Kingibe]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/kingibe-adamu-ali-mustapha-5-others-in-frame-to-succeed-kyari|title=Kingibe, Adamu, Ali, Mustapha, 5 others in frame to succeed Kyari|last1=Omonijo|first1=Bolade|last2=Alli|first2=Yusuf|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=19 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nKingibe was born to the family of Mustafa Shuwa and Ya Kingi Mallam. A [[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] from [[Borno State|Borno]], he grew up in [[Maiduguri]] and attended primary schools there. In 1958, he was admitted into the Borno Provincial Secondary School. In 1960, he left for the [[United Kingdom]] on a government scholarship to complete his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O'Level]] and [[A-level]] at [[Bishop's Stortford College]]. In 1968, he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in [[international relations]] from the [[University of Sussex]] (alongside [[Thabo Mbeki]]), before proceeding to the [[BBC Television]] Training School in London. Kingibe later received a postgraduate diploma from the [[Graduate Institute of International Studies]] in [[Geneva]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2015/07/baba-gana-kingibe-70/|title=Baba Gana Kingibe @ 70|date=2015-07-07|website=Vanguard News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n===Early career===\nIn 1969, he returned to Nigeria and was employed as a [[political science]] [[lecturer]] at the [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]]. At the university, he became acquainted with the [[Kaduna Mafia]], a group of young western-educated [[intellectuals]], [[civil servants]] and [[Nigerian Armed Forces|military officers]] from [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamji.com/haruna/haruna304.htm|title=Ibrahim Tahir: An Appreciation|last=Daura|first=Mamman|date=|website=Gamji|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Towards the end of the [[Nigerian Civil War]], Kingibe the head of the current affairs department at the Broadcasting Corporation of Northern Nigeria (BCNN).<ref name=\"ICIR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.icirnigeria.org/kyari-daura-others-in-buharis-kitchen-cabinet-have-two-things-in-common-journalism-uk-education|title=Kyari, Daura, others in Buhari\u2019s kitchen cabinet have two things in common: journalism, UK education|date=23 September 2019|accessdate=20 April 2020|last=Adebajo|first=Kunle|publisher=International Centre For Investigative Reporting}}</ref>\n\n==Diplomatic service==\nIn 1972, he joined the Nigerian Foreign Service where his first posting was the [[Nigerian High Commission in London]] as a senior political counsellor and later became the head of the political desk.<ref name=ICIR/> \n\nIn 1981, at the age of 36, he was appointed the Nigerian Ambassador to Greece and Cyprus. In 1985, Kingibe was appointed the Nigerian Ambassador to Pakistan by General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blerf.org/index.php/biography/baba-gana-kingibe/|title=BABA, Gana Kingibe|last=Admin|date=2016-11-21|website=Biographical Legacy and Research Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nKingibe also served from October 2002 to September 2006 as the [[Special Envoy]] of the [[African Union]] to [[Sudan]] and subsequently Special Representative of the [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission]] and head of the [[African Union Mission in Sudan]].<ref name=\"GaM22\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nFollowing the [[1976 Nigerian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]], Kingibe was seconded to the [[Supreme Military Council of Nigeria (1966\u20131979)|Supreme Military Headquarters]] (SMHQ) as the Principal Political Secretary, from 1976 to 1979, where he was involved in the planning of the military's transfer of power programme, [[States of Nigeria|states creation]] and [[national delimitation]], [[Local government areas of Nigeria|local government reforms]] and the [[Constitution of Nigeria#1979 constitution (Second Republic)|constitutional drafting committee]] of the [[Second Nigerian Republic]].<ref>African Concord (1990). The New Helmsmen. Concord Press, Ikeja, Lagos. August 13, 1990</ref> In this role, he simultaneously served as the Principal Political Secretary in the [[President of Nigeria|Office of the President]] between 1976 to 1981, serving both General [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] and President [[Shehu Shagari]]. Kingibe later became the [[permanent secretary]] in charge of special services within the [[Cabinet of Nigeria|Cabinet Office]], between 1981 to 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2015/07/baba-gana-kingibe-70/|title=Baba Gana Kingibe @ 70|date=2015-07-07|website=Vanguard News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Party politics===\nKingibe entered party politics in the build up to the transition of the [[Third Nigerian Republic]]. In 1988, he was made director of organization of the People's Front of Nigeria which consisted of politicians such as [[Atiku Abubakar]], [[Bola Tinubu]], [[Abdullahi Aliyu Sumaila]] and [[Rabiu Kwankwaso]], which was then led by [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/04/top-nigeria-politics-forum-liberating-nigeria|title=Top Nigeria politics forum: Liberating Nigeria|last=Sobowale|first=Rasheed|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nThe front later joined with the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]] in 1989. During the conduct of elections for national executive positions in the party, Kingibe was sponsored by the People's Front faction of SDP as the party's chairman, a position he went on to clinch. As party chairman, Kingibe was involved in the organization of party's gubernatorial and presidential primaries in 1991 and 1992 respectively.\n\n=== 1993 presidential election ===\nHowever, after the cancellations of presidential elections in 1992 in which [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua|Shehu Yar'Adua]] was a candidate, Kingibe put himself forward as a presidential candidate. He made a split from his initial camp, the PFN group and used his relationships with SDP state party chairmen to build his campaign. He lost the keenly contested primary conducted in Jos but after much prodding from SDP governors, he was selected by the primary winner, [[MKO Abiola]] as [[Vice-President of Nigeria|Vice-presidential]] running mate, creating a Muslim-Muslim ticket which was initially thought to be a deal breaker in the general elections. The pair won the electoral majority although the result was annulled by abdicating president General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref name=\"Safari Books2\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOVMBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=kingibe++pfn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI7aCfjJ3exgIVAhmSCh3o7gtX#v=onepage&q=kingibe%20%20pfn&f=false/|title=Frank Kokori: The Struggle for June 12|date=2014|publisher=Safari Books|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Abacha administration ===\nKingibe later joined the Abacha administration as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, and [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/335406-why-i-abandoned-june-12-joined-abacha-junta-kingibe.html|title=Why I abandoned June 12, joined Abacha junta - Kingibe - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2019-06-17|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary to the Government===\nIn June 2007, he was appointed [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]].<ref>Idowu Adelusi. Kingibe to move to Aso Rock Villa?. Nigerian Tribune, July 7, 2007.</ref> He was unceremoniously removed from office on September 8, 2008 by the President Umaru Yar'Adua,<ref name=\"GaM2\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref> after spreading rumors about the President's ill-health while believed to be contending for the presidency.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7604889.stm \"Nigerian leader appears in public\"] [[BBC News]]</ref>\n\n=== Buhari administration ===\nKingibe has been a powerful [[\u00c9minence grise|behind the scenes]] decision-maker in the Buhari administration, alongside chief of staff [[Abba Kyari (politician)|Abba Kyari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailycorrespondents.com.ng/2016/08/old-fox-baba-gana-kingibe-nigerias-defacto-prime-minister/|title=Old fox, Baba Gana Kingibe is Nigeria\u2019s defacto Prime Minister|last=Editor|date=2016-08-28|website=Daily Correspondents|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Country\n!Decoration\n!Presenter\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Nigeria]]\n|[[Order of the Niger|Grand Commander of the Order of the Niger]] (GCON); [[File:Ribbon bar of the Order of the Niger.gif|frameless|59x59px]]\n|[[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n|Second highest national honour in Nigeria\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://www.cfr.org/bios/9885/baba_gana_kingibe.html Biography from the Council of Foreign Relations]\n\n{{Foreign Ministers of Nigeria}}\n{{Cabinet of President Umaru Yar'Adua}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingibe, Baba Gana}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Maiduguri]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Nigeria to Greece]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Nigeria to Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Kanuri people]]\n", "name_user": "Zerzuran", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baba_Gana_Kingibe"}
{"title_page": "Town crier", "text_new": "{{short description|Officer of the court who makes public pronouncements as required by the court}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Redirect|Crier|the surname|Crier (surname)}}\n{{For|the newspaper published in Toronto|Town Crier (newspaper)}}\n{{For|the Linda Scott song|Linda Scott}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:Town Crier, Provincetown, MA.jpg|thumb|upright|Town crier of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], in 1909]]\nA '''town crier''', also called a '''bellman''',{{cn|date=June 2018}} is an [[officer]] of a [[royal court]] or [[public authority]] who makes public pronouncements as required.<ref>[[Black's Law Dictionary]]</ref>\n\n==Duties and functions==\nThe town crier was used to make public announcements in the streets. Criers often dress elaborately, by a tradition dating to the 18th century, in a red and gold coat, white breeches, black boots and a [[tricorne]] hat.\n\nIn English-speaking countries, they carried a [[handbell]] to attract people's attention, as they shouted the words \"[[Oyez]], Oyez, Oyez!\" before making their announcements. The word \"Oyez\" means \"hear ye,\" which is a call for silence and attention. ''Oyez'' derives from the [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]] word for ''listen'' (modern French, ''oyez'', infinitive, ''ou\u00efr'', but has been largely replaced by the verb ''\u00e9couter''). The proclamations book in [[Chester]] from the early 19th century records this as \"O Yes, O Yes!\"\n\n==History==\n\n===Europe===\nPrior to widespread literacy, town criers were the means of communication with the people of the town since many people could not read or write. Proclamations, local bylaws, market days, adverts, were all proclaimed by a bellman or crier.\n\nIn [[ancient Rome]], they typically proclaimed public business during the [[nundinae|market days]] that formed a kind of [[weekend]] every eight days.<ref name=homestruck>{{harvp|Struck|2009|loc=[http://www.classics.upenn.edu/myth/php/tools/dictionary.php?method=did&regexp=578 \"Nundinae\"]}}.</ref>\n\nIn Goslar, Germany, a crier was employed to remind the local populace not to urinate or defecate in the river the day before water was drawn for brewing beer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.windsortowncrier.com/twin-town-crier/ |first=Chris |last=Brown |title=Twin Town Crier helps keep the beer flowing |work=Windsor and Maidenhead Town Crier |date=19 April 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nCriers were not always men, many town criers were women.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} Bells were not the only attention-getting device\u2014in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]], a [[gong]] was the instrument of choice for many, and in [[France]] a drum was used, or a [[Horn (instrument)|hunting horn]].\n\nIn the observance of [[Allhallowtide]], \"it was customary for criers dressed in black to parade the streets, ringing a bell of mournful sound and calling on all good Christians to remember the poor [[soul in the Bible|souls]].\"<ref>''The World Review'', Volume 4, University of Minnesota, p.255.</ref>\n\n====England====\nIn order to gain the attention of the crowd, the crier would yell, \"Hear ye\" \u2013 \"[[Oyez]]\".\n[[File: Town crier Peter Moore.JPG|thumb|150px|left|upright|[[Peter Moore (town crier)|Peter Moore]], the late Town crier to the Mayor of London and The Greater London Authority.]]\nIn [[England in the Middle Ages|medieval]] [[England]], town criers were the chief means of news communication with the townspeople, since many were [[Illiteracy|illiterate]] in a period before the [[moveable type]] was invented. Royal [[proclamation]]s, local bylaws, market days, adverts, even selling [[sugarloaf|loaves of sugar]] were all proclaimed by a bellman or crier throughout the centuries\u2014at Christmas 1798, the [[Chester Canal Company]] sold some sugar damaged in their [[packet trade|packet boat]] and this was to be advertised by the bellman.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\nThe crier also escorted the destitute to the [[workhouse]], installed minor criminals in the [[stocks]] and administered [[flogging]]s. During public [[hanging]]s he read out why the person was being hanged, and helped to cut him or her down.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-04-09/news/1994099060_1_town-crier-alford-oyez |first=Carl |last=Schoettler |title=Town crier: a venerable calling that speaks volumes |newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=9 April 1994}}</ref>\n\nChester records of 1540 show fees due to the bellman included:\n{{quote|\"of every worshipful gentyllman that goyth onye gounes at ther buryall ...one goune [at funerals gowns would be given to mourners]. when he gythe or aneything that is lost ...jd [one penny]. for every bote lode with powder mellwylle [salted fish] ...one fyshe, for every boute lode with fresh fyshe that he goeth for ...jd [one penny].\"}}\n\nIn 1620, there was a fight at the Chester cross between the butchers and the bakers where the \"Cryer brake his Mace in peeces Amonge them\". In 1607, one public notice read by George Tunnall, the bellman, forbade tipping rubbish in the river.\n\nIn 1715, a local man recorded that the:\n{{quote|\"Belman at the Cross \u2026 Reads publicly a proclamation in the Mayor's name, commanding all persons in the City to be of peaceable and civil behaviour, not to walk around the Streets or Rows at unreasonable hours of night.\"}}\n\nSalmon fishing season was also closed by the bellman.<ref>''Courant'', 17 April 1792.\n:A few days ago some persons were brought before our magistrates, charged with angling and catching salmon fry in the River Dee, As the law expressly forbids the young salmon to be taken, either with nets or other engines, the bellman had orders to give notice to the inhabitants, that prosecutions would be commenced against any persons offending in the like manner.</ref><ref>''Chronicle'', 12 December 1845.\n:Illegal Fishing\n:On Saturday last, four fishermen, named William Gibson, William Hand, Robert Barlow, and William Banks, appeared at Chester Police Court, to answer an information preferred against them by Buckley, the constable appointed by the River Dee Conservancy, for being out night  fishing with illegal nets (less than 2\u00bd inches in the mesh), and also for taking unsizeable fish. The information was laid under the 1st George 1. c. 18, s.4. Immediately upon being placed before the Bench, a somewhat noisy colloquy commenced between the Supt. of Police, the court and the defendants; the latter stoutly denying that to use small nets would be to ensure the escape of all other fish. On being told that at this season of the year they could catch nothing but salmon, Barlow stated that the other night they had caught nine shillings worth of flukes, and we have good authority for saying that this statement was correct. Gibson, striking his fist on the table, solemnly swore that, \"he had not killed a salmon since they were cried down\" and another affirmed that it would be no use killing them as \"they were not fit for pigs, much less Christians.\" After a long debate between the Court and the defendants, in which the latter seemed strongly disposed to try elsewhere the right of the Magistrates to prevent them fishing with nets of any size, providing they took no salmon, a reluctant  promise was wrung from them, that they would not offend in a similar way in the future and they were discharged.</ref>\n\nThe term \"Posting A Notice\" comes from the act of the town crier, who having read his message to the townspeople, would attach it to the door post of the local inn. Some newspapers took the name \"The Post\" for this reason.\n\nTown criers were protected by law, as they sometimes brought bad news such as tax increases. Anything done by the town crier was done in the name of the ruling monarch and harming a town crier was considered to be treason.<ref name=\"BBCAug2010\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/bradford/hi/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_8931000/8931369.stm |title=Top town crier to be crowned as Hebden Bridge hits 500 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=20 August 2010}}</ref> The phrase \"[[Shooting the messenger|don't shoot the messenger]]\" was a real command.<ref name=\"BBCAug2010\"/>\n\nThere are two organizations representing town criers including the Ancient and Honourable Guild of Town Criers and Loyal Company of Town Criers.\n\nA copy of a royal proclamation announcing the [[dissolution of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]] is delivered by hand from the [[Privy Council Office (United Kingdom)|Privy Council Office]] to [[Mansion House, London|Mansion House]] in the [[City of London]]. It is then read out by the Common Crier of the City on the steps of the [[Royal Exchange, London|Royal Exchange]] in the heart of the City, having been handed to him by the Common Serjeant of the City, ahead of the proclamation also being read out in the [[London borough]]s.\n\n===North America===\n[[File:DH Burns-Morgan House.jpg|thumb|The town crier of [[St. George's, Bermuda]], Major D.H. \"Bob\" Burns, MC, the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] holder for the loudest human speaking voice, recorded on a film set, of 113 decibels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.ws/mhicgherri/garrison-images1 |title=Major Donald Henry 'Bob' Burns, MC |work=geocities.ws |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1758730/bio |title=Murray Burns - Biography |work=IMDb.com |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>]]\nThere have been town criers in North America ever since Europeans have been coming to the continent. There are records throughout the 16th century of town criers in Mexico, Peru, and Panama. During the 1830s and 40s Halifax, [[Nova Scotia]] had as many as four in the city. All through the American Colonies and beyond, such as Santa Fe, New Mexico; Boston, Massachusetts and Stamford, Connecticut had criers during the mid 17th century. In some places, the office of town crier persisted into the early 20th century. At least as recently as 1904, [[Los Angeles]] and several adjacent towns had official town criers.<ref>{{cite book |first=George Wharton |last=James |title=Travelers\u2019 handbook to southern California |url=https://archive.org/details/travelershandboo00jame |location=Pasadena, California |publisher=G.W. James |year=1904 |quote=The book provides lists of current office holders, including town criers, for several local jurisdictions.}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n====India====\nIn many parts of India, the village crier traditionally carried a rustic drum to call public attention, following up with the message. The message had a typical flow, starting with \"people of (...) village, the headman would like to announce that...\" followed by the message.\n\n====Nepal====\nIn Nepal, the town crier is called a ''katuwal'' which derives from local Tibetic, ''kat'' 'voice' + an Indic suffix ''-wal'' 'kind of person' (see TGTM *''kat'' 'voice' in <ref>{{cite book |first=Martine |last=Mazaudon |title=Consonantal mutation and tonal split in the Tamang sub-family of Tibeto-Burman. Kailash 6, 157-79. |year=1978}}</ref>). Similar to the European counterpart, the ''katuwal'' is responsible for news and other announcements in some rural villages (<ref>{{cite book |first=Rising |last=Nepal |title=Katuwal tradition still around in Sikles |year=2017}}</ref> ; <ref>{{cite book |first=Jana |last=Fortier |title=Beyond Jajmani: Indigenous labor relations of Nepal |location=Madison | publisher=Univ. of Wisconsin |year=1995}}</ref>. The town crier is paid traditionally in grain after each harvest, a portion from each family in the village. The town crier not only makes public announcements, but makes announcements in particular neighborhoods when more labor or help is needed for daily work by other families out in the fields. This ensures that labor demands are met during more intensive work activities such as harvests, weeding, and planting.\n\n====Sri Lanka====\nIn Sri Lanka, traditionally criers would carry a [[Sri Lanka drums|specific drum]] to call public attention (called tom-tom beating), following up with the message. The practice dates back from ancient times as it was used by Sri Lankan kingdoms through the colonial period up on to the modern times and was known as ''Ana Bera'' (Announcement drum beating). The practice was used by municipal or village councils until the late ninetieth century when the practice was replaced by modern communication mediums. The use of a tom-tom beating announcer is still defined in legal statutes for situations for public notification in situations such as partition of lands. It is however not practiced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/2003/10/05/featur01.html|title=featur01|website=www.island.lk|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/06/09/features/118360/rhythm-and-moves-sri-lankan-drumming|title=Rhythm and Moves with Sri Lankan drumming|website=Daily News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n[[File:Native town crier, Belgian Congo.jpg|thumb|Congolese town crier]]\nTown criers were prominent in the precolonial and colonial eras of [[Igboland]], a West African region in the present-day [[Nigeria]]. They served as the major means of information dissemination in their respective communities.\n\n==Modern town criers==\n[[File:Town Criers Thetford.jpg|thumb|260px|left|A town criers competition in [[Thetford]] in 2015]]\nWhen the need for a town crier disappeared, the position passed into local [[folklore]]. Informal and later formal town crier competitions were held from the early 20th century. Subsequently, some cities and towns reinstated the post purely for ceremonial purposes.\n\nMany local councils in England and Wales reinstated the post of town crier from the mid-1990s onwards (e.g. Chester).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chestertowncriers.com/cross-proclamation-feedback/ |title=Cross Proclamation Feedback |work=Chester Town Criers |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> Many are honorary appointments or employed part-time by the council. In October 2010, there were 144 towns in England and Wales with town criers registered with the Ancient and Honourable Guild of Town Criers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ahgtc.org.uk/ |title=Home: Promoting Prestigious Public Pronouncements |work=Ancient and Honourable Guild of Town Criers |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> They mainly perform ceremonial duties at civic functions. Local councils with a paid town crier often make them available for charity events.\n\nIn the [[Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames]], the town crier is also appointed the [[tipstaff]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingston.gov.uk/info/200233/your_mayor/488/about_the_office_of_mayor_and_other_civic_roles/2 |title=About the Office of Mayor and other civic roles |work=The Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> an appointment which exists in no other local council.\n\nIn the 2010s in England, town criers still announce the births of royal heirs and occasionally the arrival of the royal family. [[Tony Appleton]], an octogenarian and self-proclaimed \u201croyalist crier,\u201d took it upon himself to announce, as loudly as he can, important news about the royal family. Appleton has served as town crier for the nearby city of [[Romford]], but he does not represent the royal family. Appleton [https://www.yahoo.com/news/town-criers-royal-birth-cameo-confuses-us-journos-135309893.html admitted as much in 2013], when news outlets were confused by his presence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/town-crier-announces-royal-birth/|title=FACT CHECK: Did a Town Crier Announce the Royal Birth?|work=Snopes.com|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Royal baby: Town crier announces news of Prince William and Catherine's son |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23413905 |work=BBC News |date=22 July 2013 |accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Royal baby: Town crier announces birth of Royal Prince |url=http://www.windsorobserver.co.uk/news/roundup/articles/2013/07/23/91498-video-royal-borough-town-crier-welcomes-the-royal-baby-outside-windsor-castle/?mode=print |newspaper=Slough & Windsor Observer |publisher=Berkshire Media Group |accessdate=21 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130821154233/http://www.windsorobserver.co.uk/news/roundup/articles/2013/07/23/91498-video-royal-borough-town-crier-welcomes-the-royal-baby-outside-windsor-castle/?mode=print |archivedate=21 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.priory900.org/?attachment_id=3076 |title=Their Royal Highnesses the Prince of Wales and the Duchess of Cornwall visit Bridlington Priory, Tuesday 23 July |work=Bridlington Priory  |date=5 August 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/news-and-diary/the-prince-of-wales-and-the-duchess-of-cornwall-visit-yorkshire |title=Visit to Yorkshire |work=princeofwales.gov.uk |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are several town crier [[guild]]s in both [[Canada]] and the United States. These include the Ontario Guild of Town Criers, the Nova Scotia Guild of Town Criers and the American Guild of Town Criers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.towncrier.on.ca/ |title=The Ontario Guild of Town Criers |work=towncrier.on.ca |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://nsgtc.webs.com/ |title=Home |work=Nova Scotia Guild of Town Criers |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americantowncriers.com/|title=American Guild of Town Criers |work=americantowncriers.com |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the town of [[Burlingame, California]] added a town crier.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2016-02-06/calling-all-history-lovers-burlingame-announces-citys-first-official-town-crier/1776425158058.html |title=Calling all history lovers: Burlingame announces city's first official town crier |date=6 February 2016 |first=Austin |last=Walsh |newspaper=San Mateo Daily Journal |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Australia]], as of October 2010, the [[City of Sydney]], [[City of Hobart]], [[City of Greater Geelong]], [[City of Portland (Victoria)|City of Portland]], [[City of Ipswich]], [[City of Gosford]], [[City of Salisbury]], [[City of Gold Coast]] and 22 other local councils had an official town crier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://australiantowncrier.com/criers.htm |title=Town Criers in Australia |work=Ancient and Honourable Guild of Australian Town Criers}}</ref>\n\n===Competitions and records===\n[[File:Peter & Maureen Taunton.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Peter & Maureen Taunton won a Best dressed crier & lady competition in 2008<ref name=BTC/>]]\n[[Europe]]an, Canadian, American, North American and [[Australia]]n championships are held in alternating years with the World Championships.\n\nThe best dressed town crier at the World Championships in 2008 was Daniel Richer dit La Fl\u00eache representing the cities of [[Ottawa]] and [[Gatineau]], in Canada.<ref name=\"richer\">{{cite web |url= http://www.danielricher.com/ENGLISH.htm |title=Daniel Richer: Crieur public / Town crier |work=danielricher.com |year=2007 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Town crier Alan Myatt, Hitchin, UK.jpg|thumb|150px|left|upright|In 2001, [[Alan Myatt]] held the Guinness record for the world's loudest man.]]\nThe Best Dressed Couple were Peter and Maureen Taunton from the county town of [[Stafford]], in [[Staffordshire]], England.<ref name=BTC>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishtowncrier.co.uk/ |title=The British Town Crier |work=britishtowncrier.co.uk |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> Richard Riddell of Anacortes, in the state of Washington in the United States, was the 2008 American Champion and winner of the 2009 Bermuda International Town Crier Competition. He was awarded Best Dressed and tied for First Runner-up at the 2010 World Tournament at Chester in England and Overall Winner at the 2013 World Invitational Town Crier Competition held in Kingston, in Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kingstonherald.com/release/world-invitational-town-crier-competition-winners-announced-2010311849 |title=World Invitational Town Crier Competition Winners Announced |first=Robert |last=John |date=7 August 2013 |work=Kingston Herald |location=Kingston, Ontario |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nPeter Moore, the London Town Crier,<ref name=\"PMBBC\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londontowncrier.com/|title=City - News - Events - Information - Local |work=London Town Crier |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> held the position for more than 30 years. He was Town Crier to the Mayor of London,{{Clarify|date=June 2010}} the [[City of Westminster]], and [[London borough]]s, and was also a [[Freedom of the City|freeman]] and [[liveryman]] of the [[City of London]]. He died on 20 December 2009.<ref name=\"PMBBC\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/8434333.stm |title=London town crier Peter Moore dies aged 70 |date=30 December 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Alan Myatt]] holds two Guinness World Records. As well as being the loudest crier (recording a cry of 112.8 decibels),<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1396836.stm |title=Quiet night's sleep for 'world's loudest man' |date=19 June 2001 |work=[[BBC Online]] |accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> he also set the record for vocal endurance, issuing a one-hundred word proclamation every 15 minutes for a period of 48 hours.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gloucestercitizen.co.uk/Oyez-Oyez-Town-crier-Alan-Myatt-rings-25-years/story-18938044-detail/story.html |title=Oyez! Oyez! Town crier Alan Myatt rings in 25 years of service |date=9 May 2013 |newspaper=[[The Citizen (Gloucester)|Gloucester Citizen]] |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414163321/http://www.gloucestercitizen.co.uk/Oyez-Oyez-Town-crier-Alan-Myatt-rings-25-years/story-18938044-detail/story.html |archivedate=14 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDaniel Richer dit La Fl\u00eache, who is a member of the [[First Nations]] [[Abenaki]] tribe, is a full-time bilingual town crier.<ref name=\"richer\"/> David Hinde, Bridlington Town Crier, was measured at 114.8 decibels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Hear-ye-m-loudest-crier-land/story-19709039-detail/story.html#ixzz2yaVDfEhI. |title=Hear ye! I'm loudest crier in all the land |date=26 August 2013 |newspaper=Hull Daily Mail |accessdate=14 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924032132/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Hear-ye-m-loudest-crier-land/story-19709039-detail/story.html#ixzz2yaVDfEhI. |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTaking place from the 20th to 23 August 2014, Chris Whyman from Kingston, Ontario, Canada, was declared the winner of the 2014 World Town Crier Tournament in Chester.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chesterchronicle.co.uk/news/chester-cheshire-news/world-town-crier-tournament-chester-7678828 |title=World Town Crier Tournament Chester: Final |first=Jo |last=Henwood |date=27 August 2014 |work=Chester Chronicle |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewhig.com/2014/08/25/whyman-world-champion-again |title=Whyman world champion again |date=25 August 2014 |work=The Kingston Whig-Standard |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Paddy-Ann Pemberton hosted an International World Town Crier Invitational Tournament over seven days in Central Otago. The three days of competition produced Ken Knowles of Lichfield, England as the winner, Jerry Praver (USA) was second, Daniel Richer Dit La Fleche (Ottawa) was third. Knowles won each of the daily competitions held at three different venues: Alexandra, Roxburgh and Cromwell, all in Central Otago, New Zealand.\n\nIn September 2017, Gary Long, with some assistance from Lloyd Smith and Peter Davies, hosted the same International Invitational Competition in the Annapolis Valley of Nova Scotia, Canada. Nineteen top town criers came from Australia, New Zealand, California, Maryland, Ontario, Nova Scotia and England to compete in the three round event. The rounds were held in Windsor, Annapolis Royal and Grand Pre. Mark Molnar of St. Catharines Ontario won. Paul Gough of Nuneaton and Bedworth England came second and Daniel Richer dit LaFleche came third.\n\n;Australia\nThe 25th Annual National Town Crier Championships was hosted by Redland City Council and Redland Town Crier Maxwell Bissett in Redland City on 3 September 2016. The competition took place as part of the Redland Spring Festival, RedFest. Members of the Ancient and Honourable Guild of Australian Town Criers competed for champion titles. The 2016 theme of the competition is \"The History and Diversity of the Redlands.\"\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dead bell]], used to announce deaths and funerals.\n* [[Street cries]]\n* [[Umalohokan]]\n* [[Vic Garth]], reputed in 2005 to be the oldest town crier in the world.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gordon Emery, ''Curious Chester'' (1999) {{ISBN|1-872265-94-4}}\n* David Mitchell, ''For Crying Out Loud: The Story of the Town Crier and Bellman, Past and Present'' (2010) {{ISBN|978-1-905575-10-7}}\n* David Mitchell, \"The Word on the Street: A History of the Town Crier and Bellman\" (2019) {{ISBN|978-1-9160047-02}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Town criers}}http://www.loyalcompanyoftowncriers.co.uk/<nowiki/>The Loyal Company of Town Criers (UK)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Town Crier}}\n[[Category:Media occupations]]\n[[Category:Obsolete occupations]]\n[[Category:Town criers|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Officer of the court who makes public pronouncements as required by the court}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Redirect|Crier|the surname|Crier (surname)}}\n{{For|the newspaper published in Toronto|Town Crier (newspaper)}}\n{{For|the Linda Scott song|Linda Scott}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:Town Crier, Provincetown, MA.jpg|thumb|upright|Town crier of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], in 1909]]\nA '''town crier''', also called a '''bellman''',{{cn|date=June 2018}} is an [[officer]] of a [[royal court]] or [[public authority]] who makes public pronouncements as required.<ref>[[Black's Law Dictionary]]</ref>\n\n==Duties and functions==\nThe town crier was used to make public announcements in the streets. Criers often dress elaborately, by a tradition dating to the 18th century, in a red and gold coat, white breeches, black boots and a [[tricorne]] hat.\n\nIn English-speaking countries, they carried a [[handbell]] to attract people's attention, as they shouted the words \"[[Oyez]], Oyez, Oyez!\" before making their announcements. The word \"Oyez\" means \"hear ye,\" which is a call for silence and attention. ''Oyez'' derives from the [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]] word for ''listen'' (modern French, ''oyez'', infinitive, ''ou\u00efr'', but has been largely replaced by the verb ''\u00e9couter''). The proclamations book in [[Chester]] from the early 19th century records this as \"O Yes, O Yes!\"\n\n==History==\n\n===Europe===\nPrior to widespread literacy, town criers were the means of communication with the people of the town since many people could not read or write. Proclamations, local bylaws, market days, adverts, were all proclaimed by a bellman or crier.\n\nIn [[ancient Rome]], they typically proclaimed public business during the [[nundinae|market days]] that formed a kind of [[weekend]] every eight days.<ref name=homestruck>{{harvp|Struck|2009|loc=[http://www.classics.upenn.edu/myth/php/tools/dictionary.php?method=did&regexp=578 \"Nundinae\"]}}.</ref>\n\nIn Goslar, Germany, a crier was employed to remind the local populace not to urinate or defecate in the river the day before water was drawn for brewing beer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.windsortowncrier.com/twin-town-crier/ |first=Chris |last=Brown |title=Twin Town Crier helps keep the beer flowing |work=Windsor and Maidenhead Town Crier |date=19 April 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nCriers were not always men, many town criers were women.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} Bells were not the only attention-getting device\u2014in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]], a [[gong]] was the instrument of choice for many, and in [[France]] a drum was used, or a [[Horn (instrument)|hunting horn]].\n\nIn the observance of [[Allhallowtide]], \"it was customary for criers dressed in black to parade the streets, ringing a bell of mournful sound and calling on all good Christians to remember the poor [[soul in the Bible|souls]].\"<ref>''The World Review'', Volume 4, University of Minnesota, p.255.</ref>\n\n====England====\nIn order to gain the attention of the crowd, the crier would yell, \"Hear ye\" \u2013 \"[[Oyez]]\".\n[[File: Town crier Peter Moore.JPG|thumb|150px|left|upright|[[Peter Moore (town crier)|Peter Moore]], the late Town crier to the Mayor of London and The Greater London Authority.]]\nIn [[England in the Middle Ages|medieval]] [[England]], town criers were the chief means of news communication with the townspeople, since many were [[Illiteracy|illiterate]] in a period before the [[moveable type]] was invented. Royal [[proclamation]]s, local bylaws, market days, adverts, even selling [[sugarloaf|loaves of sugar]] were all proclaimed by a bellman or crier throughout the centuries\u2014at Christmas 1798, the [[Chester Canal Company]] sold some sugar damaged in their [[packet trade|packet boat]] and this was to be advertised by the bellman.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\nThe crier also escorted the destitute to the [[workhouse]], installed minor criminals in the [[stocks]] and administered [[flogging]]s. During public [[hanging]]s he read out why the person was being hanged, and helped to cut him or her down.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-04-09/news/1994099060_1_town-crier-alford-oyez |first=Carl |last=Schoettler |title=Town crier: a venerable calling that speaks volumes |newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=9 April 1994}}</ref>\n\nChester records of 1540 show fees due to the bellman included:\n{{quote|\"of every worshipful gentyllman that goyth onye gounes at ther buryall ...one goune [at funerals gowns would be given to mourners]. when he gythe or aneything that is lost ...jd [one penny]. for every bote lode with powder mellwylle [salted fish] ...one fyshe, for every boute lode with fresh fyshe that he goeth for ...jd [one penny].\"}}\n\nIn 1620, there was a fight at the Chester cross between the butchers and the bakers where the \"Cryer brake his Mace in peeces Amonge them\". In 1607, one public notice read by George Tunnall, the bellman, forbade tipping rubbish in the river.\n\nIn 1715, a local man recorded that the:\n{{quote|\"Belman at the Cross \u2026 Reads publicly a proclamation in the Mayor's name, commanding all persons in the City to be of peaceable and civil behaviour, not to walk around the Streets or Rows at unreasonable hours of night.\"}}\n\nSalmon fishing season was also closed by the bellman.<ref>''Courant'', 17 April 1792.\n:A few days ago some persons were brought before our magistrates, charged with angling and catching salmon fry in the River Dee, As the law expressly forbids the young salmon to be taken, either with nets or other engines, the bellman had orders to give notice to the inhabitants, that prosecutions would be commenced against any persons offending in the like manner.</ref><ref>''Chronicle'', 12 December 1845.\n:Illegal Fishing\n:On Saturday last, four fishermen, named William Gibson, William Hand, Robert Barlow, and William Banks, appeared at Chester Police Court, to answer an information preferred against them by Buckley, the constable appointed by the River Dee Conservancy, for being out night  fishing with illegal nets (less than 2\u00bd inches in the mesh), and also for taking unsizeable fish. The information was laid under the 1st George 1. c. 18, s.4. Immediately upon being placed before the Bench, a somewhat noisy colloquy commenced between the Supt. of Police, the court and the defendants; the latter stoutly denying that to use small nets would be to ensure the escape of all other fish. On being told that at this season of the year they could catch nothing but salmon, Barlow stated that the other night they had caught nine shillings worth of flukes, and we have good authority for saying that this statement was correct. Gibson, striking his fist on the table, solemnly swore that, \"he had not killed a salmon since they were cried down\" and another affirmed that it would be no use killing them as \"they were not fit for pigs, much less Christians.\" After a long debate between the Court and the defendants, in which the latter seemed strongly disposed to try elsewhere the right of the Magistrates to prevent them fishing with nets of any size, providing they took no salmon, a reluctant  promise was wrung from them, that they would not offend in a similar way in the future and they were discharged.</ref>\n\nThe term \"Posting A Notice\" comes from the act of the town crier, who having read his message to the townspeople, would attach it to the door post of the local inn. Some newspapers took the name \"The Post\" for this reason.\n\nTown criers were protected by law, as they sometimes brought bad news such as tax increases. Anything done by the town crier was done in the name of the ruling monarch and harming a town crier was considered to be treason.<ref name=\"BBCAug2010\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/bradford/hi/people_and_places/arts_and_culture/newsid_8931000/8931369.stm |title=Top town crier to be crowned as Hebden Bridge hits 500 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=20 August 2010}}</ref> The phrase \"[[Shooting the messenger|don't shoot the messenger]]\" was a real command.<ref name=\"BBCAug2010\"/>\n\nThere are two organizations representing town criers including the Ancient and Honourable Guild of Town Criers and Loyal Company of Town Criers.\n\nA copy of a royal proclamation announcing the [[dissolution of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]] is delivered by hand from the [[Privy Council Office (United Kingdom)|Privy Council Office]] to [[Mansion House, London|Mansion House]] in the [[City of London]]. It is then read out by the Common Crier of the City on the steps of the [[Royal Exchange, London|Royal Exchange]] in the heart of the City, having been handed to him by the Common Serjeant of the City, ahead of the proclamation also being read out in the [[London borough]]s.\n\n===North America===\n[[File:DH Burns-Morgan House.jpg|thumb|The town crier of [[St. George's, Bermuda]], Major D.H. \"Bob\" Burns, MC, the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] holder for the loudest human speaking voice, recorded on a film set, of 113 decibels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.ws/mhicgherri/garrison-images1 |title=Major Donald Henry 'Bob' Burns, MC |work=geocities.ws |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1758730/bio |title=Murray Burns - Biography |work=IMDb.com |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>]]\nThere have been town criers in North America ever since Europeans have been coming to the continent. There are records throughout the 16th century of town criers in Mexico, Peru, and Panama. During the 1830s and 40s Halifax, [[Nova Scotia]] had as many as four in the city. All through the American Colonies and beyond, such as Santa Fe, New Mexico; Boston, Massachusetts and Stamford, Connecticut had criers during the mid 17th century. In some places, the office of town crier persisted into the early 20th century. At least as recently as 1904, [[Los Angeles]] and several adjacent towns had official town criers.<ref>{{cite book |first=George Wharton |last=James |title=Travelers\u2019 handbook to southern California |url=https://archive.org/details/travelershandboo00jame |location=Pasadena, California |publisher=G.W. James |year=1904 |quote=The book provides lists of current office holders, including town criers, for several local jurisdictions.}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n====India====\nIn many parts of India, the village crier traditionally carried a rustic drum to call public attention, following up with the message. The message had a typical flow, starting with \"people of (...) village, the headman would like to announce that...\" followed by the message.\n\n====Nepal====\nIn Nepal, the town crier is called a ''katuwal'' which derives from local Tibetic, ''kat'' 'voice' + an Indic suffix ''-wal'' 'kind of person' (see TGTM *''kat'' 'voice' in <ref>{{cite book |first=Martine |last=Mazaudon |title=Consonantal mutation and tonal split in the Tamang sub-family of Tibeto-Burman. Kailash 6, 157-79. |year=1978}}</ref>). Similar to the European counterpart, the ''katuwal'' is responsible for news and other announcements in some rural villages (<ref>{{cite book |first=Rising |last=Nepal |title=Katuwal tradition still around in Sikles |year=2017}}</ref> ; <ref>{{cite book |first=Jana |last=Fortier |title=Beyond Jajmani: Indigenous labor relations of Nepal |location=Madison | publisher=Univ. of Wisconsin |year=1995}}</ref>. The town crier is paid traditionally in grain after each harvest, a portion from each family in the village. The town crier not only makes public announcements, but makes announcements in particular neighborhoods when more labor or help is needed for daily work by other families out in the fields. This ensures that labor demands are met during more intensive work activities such as harvests, weeding, and planting.\n\n====Sri Lanka====\nIn Sri Lanka, traditionally criers would carry a [[Sri Lanka drums|specific drum]] to call public attention (called tom-tom beating), following up with the message. The practice dates back from ancient times as it was used by Sri Lankan kingdoms through the colonial period up on to the modern times and was known as ''Ana Bera'' (Announcement drum beating). The practice was used by municipal or village councils until the late ninetieth century when the practice was replaced by modern communication mediums. The use of a tom-tom beating announcer is still defined in legal statutes for situations for public notification in situations such as partition of lands. It is however not practiced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/2003/10/05/featur01.html|title=featur01|website=www.island.lk|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2017/06/09/features/118360/rhythm-and-moves-sri-lankan-drumming|title=Rhythm and Moves with Sri Lankan drumming|website=Daily News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n[[File:Native town crier, Belgian Congo.jpg|thumb|Congolese town crier]]\nTown criers were prominent in the precolonial and colonial eras of [[Igboland]], a West African region in the present-day [[Nigeria]]. They served as the major means of information dissemination in their respective communities.\n\n==Modern town criers==\n[[File:Town Criers Thetford.jpg|thumb|260px|left|A town criers competition in [[Thetford]] in 2015]]\nWhen the need for a town crier disappeared, the position passed into local [[folklore]]. Informal and later formal town crier competitions were held from the early 20th century. Subsequently, some cities and towns reinstated the post purely for ceremonial purposes.\n\nMany local councils in England and Wales reinstated the post of town crier from the mid-1990s onwards (e.g. Chester).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chestertowncriers.com/cross-proclamation-feedback/ |title=Cross Proclamation Feedback |work=Chester Town Criers |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> Many are honorary appointments or employed part-time by the council. In October 2010, there were 144 towns in England and Wales with town criers registered with the Ancient and Honourable Guild of Town Criers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ahgtc.org.uk/ |title=Home: Promoting Prestigious Public Pronouncements |work=Ancient and Honourable Guild of Town Criers |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> They mainly perform ceremonial duties at civic functions. Local councils with a paid town crier often make them available for charity events.\n\nIn the [[Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames]], the town crier is also appointed the [[tipstaff]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingston.gov.uk/info/200233/your_mayor/488/about_the_office_of_mayor_and_other_civic_roles/2 |title=About the Office of Mayor and other civic roles |work=The Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> an appointment which exists in no other local council.\n\nIn the 2010s in England, town criers still announce the births of royal heirs and occasionally the arrival of the royal family. [[Tony Appleton]], an octogenarian and self-proclaimed \u201croyalist crier,\u201d took it upon himself to announce, as loudly as he can, important news about the royal family. Appleton has served as town crier for the nearby city of [[Romford]], but he does not represent the royal family. Appleton [https://www.yahoo.com/news/town-criers-royal-birth-cameo-confuses-us-journos-135309893.html admitted as much in 2013], when news outlets were confused by his presence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/town-crier-announces-royal-birth/|title=FACT CHECK: Did a Town Crier Announce the Royal Birth?|work=Snopes.com|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Royal baby: Town crier announces news of Prince William and Catherine's son |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23413905 |work=BBC News |date=22 July 2013 |accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Royal baby: Town crier announces birth of Royal Prince |url=http://www.windsorobserver.co.uk/news/roundup/articles/2013/07/23/91498-video-royal-borough-town-crier-welcomes-the-royal-baby-outside-windsor-castle/?mode=print |newspaper=Slough & Windsor Observer |publisher=Berkshire Media Group |accessdate=21 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130821154233/http://www.windsorobserver.co.uk/news/roundup/articles/2013/07/23/91498-video-royal-borough-town-crier-welcomes-the-royal-baby-outside-windsor-castle/?mode=print |archivedate=21 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.priory900.org/?attachment_id=3076 |title=Their Royal Highnesses the Prince of Wales and the Duchess of Cornwall visit Bridlington Priory, Tuesday 23 July |work=Bridlington Priory  |date=5 August 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/news-and-diary/the-prince-of-wales-and-the-duchess-of-cornwall-visit-yorkshire |title=Visit to Yorkshire |work=princeofwales.gov.uk |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are several town crier [[guild]]s in both [[Canada]] and the United States. These include the Ontario Guild of Town Criers, the Nova Scotia Guild of Town Criers and the American Guild of Town Criers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.towncrier.on.ca/ |title=The Ontario Guild of Town Criers |work=towncrier.on.ca |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://nsgtc.webs.com/ |title=Home |work=Nova Scotia Guild of Town Criers |year=2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americantowncriers.com/|title=American Guild of Town Criers |work=americantowncriers.com |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the town of [[Burlingame, California]] added a town crier.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2016-02-06/calling-all-history-lovers-burlingame-announces-citys-first-official-town-crier/1776425158058.html |title=Calling all history lovers: Burlingame announces city's first official town crier |date=6 February 2016 |first=Austin |last=Walsh |newspaper=San Mateo Daily Journal |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Australia]], as of October 2010, the [[City of Sydney]], [[City of Hobart]], [[City of Greater Geelong]], [[City of Portland (Victoria)|City of Portland]], [[City of Ipswich]], [[City of Gosford]], [[City of Salisbury]], [[City of Gold Coast]] and 22 other local councils had an official town crier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://australiantowncrier.com/criers.htm |title=Town Criers in Australia |work=Ancient and Honourable Guild of Australian Town Criers}}</ref>\n\n===Competitions and records===\n[[File:Peter & Maureen Taunton.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Peter & Maureen Taunton won a Best dressed crier & lady competition in 2008<ref name=BTC/>]]\n[[Europe]]an, Canadian, American, North American and [[Australia]]n championships are held in alternating years with the World Championships.\n\nThe best dressed town crier at the World Championships in 2008 was Daniel Richer dit La Fl\u00eache representing the cities of [[Ottawa]] and [[Gatineau]], in Canada.<ref name=\"richer\">{{cite web |url= http://www.danielricher.com/ENGLISH.htm |title=Daniel Richer: Crieur public / Town crier |work=danielricher.com |year=2007 |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Town crier Alan Myatt, Hitchin, UK.jpg|thumb|150px|left|upright|In 2001, [[Alan Myatt]] held the Guinness record for the world's loudest man.]]\nThe Best Dressed Couple were Peter and Maureen Taunton from the county town of [[Stafford]], in [[Staffordshire]], England.<ref name=BTC>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishtowncrier.co.uk/ |title=The British Town Crier |work=britishtowncrier.co.uk |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> Richard Riddell of Anacortes, in the state of Washington in the United States, was the 2008 American Champion and winner of the 2009 Bermuda International Town Crier Competition. He was awarded Best Dressed and tied for First Runner-up at the 2010 World Tournament at Chester in England and Overall Winner at the 2013 World Invitational Town Crier Competition held in Kingston, in Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kingstonherald.com/release/world-invitational-town-crier-competition-winners-announced-2010311849 |title=World Invitational Town Crier Competition Winners Announced |first=Robert |last=John |date=7 August 2013 |work=Kingston Herald |location=Kingston, Ontario |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nPeter Moore, the London Town Crier,<ref name=\"PMBBC\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londontowncrier.com/|title=City - News - Events - Information - Local |work=London Town Crier |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> held the position for more than 30 years. He was Town Crier to the Mayor of London,{{Clarify|date=June 2010}} the [[City of Westminster]], and [[London borough]]s, and was also a [[Freedom of the City|freeman]] and [[liveryman]] of the [[City of London]]. He died on 20 December 2009.<ref name=\"PMBBC\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/8434333.stm |title=London town crier Peter Moore dies aged 70 |date=30 December 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Alan Myatt]] holds two Guinness World Records. As well as being the loudest crier (recording a cry of 112.8 decibels),<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1396836.stm |title=Quiet night's sleep for 'world's loudest man' |date=19 June 2001 |work=[[BBC Online]] |accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> he also set the record for vocal endurance, issuing a one-hundred word proclamation every 15 minutes for a period of 48 hours.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gloucestercitizen.co.uk/Oyez-Oyez-Town-crier-Alan-Myatt-rings-25-years/story-18938044-detail/story.html |title=Oyez! Oyez! Town crier Alan Myatt rings in 25 years of service |date=9 May 2013 |newspaper=[[The Citizen (Gloucester)|Gloucester Citizen]] |accessdate=14 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414163321/http://www.gloucestercitizen.co.uk/Oyez-Oyez-Town-crier-Alan-Myatt-rings-25-years/story-18938044-detail/story.html |archivedate=14 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDaniel Richer dit La Fl\u00eache, who is a member of the [[First Nations]] [[Abenaki]] tribe, is a full-time bilingual town crier.<ref name=\"richer\"/> David Hinde, Bridlington Town Crier, was measured at 114.8 decibels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Hear-ye-m-loudest-crier-land/story-19709039-detail/story.html#ixzz2yaVDfEhI. |title=Hear ye! I'm loudest crier in all the land |date=26 August 2013 |newspaper=Hull Daily Mail |accessdate=14 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924032132/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Hear-ye-m-loudest-crier-land/story-19709039-detail/story.html#ixzz2yaVDfEhI. |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTaking place from the 20th to 23 August 2014, Chris Whyman from Kingston, Ontario, Canada, was declared the winner of the 2014 World Town Crier Tournament in Chester.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chesterchronicle.co.uk/news/chester-cheshire-news/world-town-crier-tournament-chester-7678828 |title=World Town Crier Tournament Chester: Final |first=Jo |last=Henwood |date=27 August 2014 |work=Chester Chronicle |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewhig.com/2014/08/25/whyman-world-champion-again |title=Whyman world champion again |date=25 August 2014 |work=The Kingston Whig-Standard |accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Paddy-Ann Pemberton hosted an International World Town Crier Invitational Tournament over seven days in Central Otago. The three days of competition produced Ken Knowles of Lichfield, England as the winner, Jerry Praver (USA) was second, Daniel Richer Dit La Fleche (Ottawa) was third. Knowles won each of the daily competitions held at three different venues: Alexandra, Roxburgh and Cromwell, all in Central Otago, New Zealand.\n\nIn September 2017, Gary Long, with some assistance from Lloyd Smith and Peter Davies, hosted the same International Invitational Competition in the Annapolis Valley of Nova Scotia, Canada. Nineteen top town criers came from Australia, New Zealand, California, Maryland, Ontario, Nova Scotia and England to compete in the three round event. The rounds were held in Windsor, Annapolis Royal and Grand Pre. Mark Molnar of St. Catharines Ontario won. Paul Gough of Nuneaton and Bedworth England came second and Daniel Richer dit LaFleche came third.\n\n;Australia\nThe 25th Annual National Town Crier Championships was hosted by Redland City Council and Redland Town Crier Maxwell Bissett in Redland City on 3 September 2016. The competition took place as part of the Redland Spring Festival, RedFest. Members of the Ancient and Honourable Guild of Australian Town Criers competed for champion titles. The 2016 theme of the competition is \"The History and Diversity of the Redlands.\"\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dead bell]], used to announce deaths and funerals.\n* [[Street cries]]\n* [[Umalohokan]]\n* [[Vic Garth]], reputed in 2005 to be the oldest town crier in the world.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gordon Emery, ''Curious Chester'' (1999) {{ISBN|1-872265-94-4}}\n* David Mitchell, ''For Crying Out Loud: The Story of the Town Crier and Bellman, Past and Present'' (2010) {{ISBN|978-1-905575-10-7}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Town criers}}http://www.loyalcompanyoftowncriers.co.uk/<nowiki/>The Loyal Company of Town Criers (UK)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Town Crier}}\n[[Category:Media occupations]]\n[[Category:Obsolete occupations]]\n[[Category:Town criers|*]]\n", "name_user": "Chestercrier", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Town_crier"}
{"title_page": "Empire of Dreams (poetry collection)", "text_new": "{{short description|Epic poetry book by Giannina Braschi}}\n{{Italic title}}\n'''''Empire of Dreams''''' ({{lang-es|El imperio de los sue\u00f1os}}, 1988) is a [[postmodern]] poetry epic by Puerto Rican author [[Giannina Braschi]], who is considered \"one of the most [[revolutionary]] voices in [[Latin American literature]] today\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi|title=Giannina Braschi|work=National Book Festival|publisher=Library of Congress|year=2012|quote=\"Braschi, one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Modern Language Association Presents Giannina Braschi|quote =\"Considered one of the most revolutionary Latin American poets writing today, Giannina Braschi, author of the epic prose poem 'Empire of Dreams'.\"|url=http://circumferencemag.org/?event=modern-language-association-presents-giannina-braschi|website=Circumference Magazine: Poetry in Translation, Academy of American Poets|date =January 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=World Literature in Translation: Giannina Braschi's Empire of Dreams|url=http://yalepress.yale.edu/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959&printer=y|website=Yale University Press|quote=\"Braschi's book is a modern classic, informed with all of the major concerns of our contemporary culture.\"|date=August 1994|access-date=2015-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091257/http://yalepress.yale.edu/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959&printer=y|archive-date=2015-05-18|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=PEN: Free Expression/Literature|url=https://www.pen.org/giannina-braschi|website=PEN American Center|quote=\"Giannina Braschi, one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today, wrote the postmodern poetry classic EMPIRE OF DREAMS.\"|date=November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=D'Amore|author2=Anna Maria|title='Translating Contemporary Mexican Texts: Fidelity to Alterity'|quote=\"In the stakes of literary acclaim and respectability is Giannina Braschi, considered by many to be Puerto Rico's premier poet.\"|publisher=Berkeley Insights in Linguistics and Semiotics|place=New York|page=104|date=2009}}</ref> Her third collection of poetry in Spanish, it was published in 1988 in Spain to acclaim as ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os.'' \n\nIt was later combined with her first two poetry collections, translated into English by Tess O'Dwyer, and the trilogy was published in 1994 as ''Empire of Dreams,'' the first volume of the [[Yale]] Library of World Literature in Translation.<ref>{{Citation|last=Barnstone|first1=Willis|title=Literature of Asia, Africa, and Latin America: From Antiquity to the Present|quote=\"Empire of Dreams is an epic length sequence of poems published to acclaim\".../\"brightest new voice in her generation in the Spanish language.\"|place=Saddle River, NJ|publisher=Prentice Hall|page=1954|date=1994}}</ref> Composed from 1980 to 1986, this trilogy represents the first major phase of Braschi's [[Work of art|oeuvre]]: poetry written entirely in classical and modern Spanish.\n\nThe trilogy is a hybrid of genres: [[prose poetry]], [[drama]], [[musical theater]], [[manifesto]], [[gossip]], [[autobiography]], [[diary]], [[literary theory]], and [[antinovel]]. The central axis of this [[epic poem]] is the Latin American [[immigrant]]'s optimistic new life in the \"[[Big Apple]]\" (New York City), which is dramatized by Braschi as the epicenter of the [[American Dream]]. Social and linguistic references to Latin American cities and neighborhoods also abound, such as \"the Latin American Quarter in Paris, the ''barrio chino barcelon\u00e9s'', the ''zaguanes'' of Borges's Buenos Aires, and the colonial houses in Old San Juan\".<ref>{{cite journal|authorlink=Carrion, Maria Mercedes|title='Geography, (M)Other Tongues and the Role of Translation in Giannina Braschi's El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'|quote= \"the Latin American Quarter in Paris, the ''barrio chino barcelon\u00e9s'', the ''zaguanes'' of Borges's Buenos Aires, and the colonial houses in Old San Juan\".|journal=Studies in 20th Century Literature|volume=20|pages=167\u2013192|date=1996}}</ref>\n\n==Subject, structure, and themes==\n''Empire of Dreams'' deals with issues of artistic creation, [[immigration]], commercialism, [[capitalism]], [[identity crisis]], sexual and gender ambiguity, and [[revolution]]. The narrator journeys through a \"phantasmagoria of internal and external trials in order to experience the center\u2014of political power, of meaning, of feeling, and of personal identity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yalebooks.com/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959|title=Yale University Press Reviews|quote=\"New York City becomes the site of liberation for its marginal citizens, as the narrator is led through a seeming phantasmagoria of internal and external trials in order to experience the center\u2014of political power, of meaning, of feeling, and of personal identity.\"|date=August 1994|access-date=2015-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619011053/http://www.yalebooks.com/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959|archive-date=2015-06-19|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe work has been compared structurally to the [[Chinese boxes|Chinese box]] and the [[Matryoshka doll]]. It contains six books.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title= Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Literature|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Hispanic-American Literature|volume=5|pages=429|publisher=Infobase Learning|date=August 31, 2008|isbn =9781438140605}}</ref>\n\nPart one, \"Assault on Time\", is a sequence of meditative prose poems on the subject of love lost and the ineptitude of language and grammar to communicate emotions. It was published in 1980 as Braschi's first book of poetry in Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/2012/09/14/1ea74c24-f2e4-11e1-a612-3cfc842a6d89mar_story.html/|title=The Washington Post|quote=\"Giannina Braschi's first published work was a book of poetry, 'Asalto al tiempo'; since then she has had essays, a novella and more poetry published in Spanish. She went on to write the novel 'Yo-Yo Boing!' in [[Spanglish]]. Her new novel is her first in English 'United States of Banana.'|date=November 2012}}</ref> It begins with the breaking of silence: \"Behind the word is silence./Behind what sounds is the door\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Braschi, Giannina|title='Empire of Dreams' translated by Tess O'Dwyer|quote=\"Behind the word is silence./Behind what sounds is the door\"|publisher=Yale University Press|place=New Haven, CT|page=1|isbn=9780300057959|date=1994}}</ref> Letters take on a life of their own, roaming the streets of New York, and punctuation marks, such as [[Colon (punctuation)|colons]] and [[semicolon]]s, denote pivotal points in a relationship.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Literature|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Hispanic-American Literature|volume=5|pages=429|publisher=Infobase Learning|date=August 31, 2008|isbn =9781438140605}}</ref>\n\nPart two, \"Profane Comedy\", was also published first in Spanish, in 1985. It becomes \"loud\", as the poet pays homage to the evolution of poetry and performance, especially [[comedia dell'arte]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Ostriker|first=Alicia|title=Introduction to Empire of Dreams|quote=\"Profane Comedy is an homage to performance, especially comedia dell'arte.\"|place=New Haven, CT|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=x-xx1|date=1994}}</ref> \"Profane Comedy\" is composed of four books of poetry, each with humorous gusto and a flair for the grotesque: 1. \"Book of Clowns and Buffoons\", 2. \"Poems of the World; or The Book of Wisdom\", 3. \"Pastoral; or, The Inquisition of Memories\", and 4. \"Song of Nothingness\". Throughout, Braschi intermingles television [[jingles]] and pop songs by such singers as [[The Beatles]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] with poems of the [[Spanish Golden Age]]. References include [[Luis de Le\u00f3n]], [[Miguel de Cervantes]], [[Lope de Vega]], [[Luis de G\u00f3ngora]], [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso de la Vega]], and [[Francisco Quevedo]], while cameo appearances are made by poets, painters, philosophers, and composers, such as: [[C\u00e9sar Vallejo]], [[Rimbaud]], [[Goethe]], [[Nietzsche]], [[Shakespeare]], [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder|Breughal]], [[Beethoven]], [[Van Gogh]], and [[Picasso]], among others. She liberally quotes from classical poets, transformed by her use of the \"sampling technique of rap music\" and [[hip hop]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Ostriker|first=Alicia|title=Introduction to ''Empire of Dreams''|place=New Haven, CT|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=x-xx1|date=1994}}</ref> Though Braschi writes with a strong literary tradition behind her and from an erudite standpoint, \"she imbues her text with jollity and a brilliant energy\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Kuebler|first=Caroline|title=\"Empire of Dreams\" Review|quote=\"Braschi writes with a strong poetic tradition behind her, and from her erudite standpoint she forges an odd mixture of poetry, prose, drama, and a little of what could be considered music. She imbues her text with jollity and a brilliant energy that stretches its audience from lovers of modernism to seekers of a broadened artistry of language.\"|publisher=Review of Contemporary Fiction|place=Dalkey Archives, Champaign, Il|date=August 1994}}</ref> \n\nThe text unfolds through a series of violent and [[surrealism|surreal]]<ref>{{Citation|last=Barnstone|first1= Willis|title=Literature of Latin America|quote=\"Braschi is a Spanish Arthur Rimbaud reinventing surrealism, creating a modern classic\"|place=Princeton|publisher=Prentice Hall|page=460|date=2002}}</ref> theatrical scenes performed by clowns, buffoons, shepherds, lead soldiers, magicians, madmen, witches, and fortune tellers. These gender-bending immigrant characters attack and occupy the American mainstream, including business centers and tourist attractions.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Cruz Malave, Arnaldo|title=Under the Skirt of Liberty: Giannina Braschi Rewrites Empire|journal=American Quarterly|volume=66.3|pages=801\u2013818|date=2015}}</ref> In a climactic episode of \"[[Pastoral]]; or, the [[Inquisition]] of Memories\", shepherds cause traffic jams on [[Fifth Avenue|5th Avenue]] during the [[Puerto Rican Day Parade]], ring the bells of [[St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)|St. Patrick's Cathedral]], and take over the observation deck of the [[Empire State Building]]. There they dance and sing: \"Now we do whatever we please, whatever we please, whatever we damn well please\".\n\nPart three, \"Intimate Diary of Solitude,\" is a lighthearted [[antinovel]] that mocks the [[Latin American Boom]] and [[dictator novel]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/39r0x1rq|title=Arellano, Jer\u00f3nimo. Magical Realism and the History of the Emotions in Latin America. Lewisburg, PA: Bucknell University Press, 2015. Print. 211 pp.|website=escholarship.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The composition is a mix-mash of [[flash fiction]], pop songs, [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]], [[Advertising|commercials]], diary excerpts, political and literary [[manifestos]], and performance art, closing with a philosophical treatise on the writer's role in the modern age. The heroine Mariquita Samper, a [[Macy's]] make-up artist who dreams of being a star, calls for a revolution of \"poetic eggs\" and shoots the [[narrator]] of Latin American Boom novels (such as ''[[One Hundred Years of Solitude]]''), who keeps rewriting her own diary in order to turn it into a bestseller.<ref>{{Citation|last=Marting|first1=Diane|title= New/Nueva York in Giannina Braschi's 'Poetic Egg': Fragile Identity, Postmodernism, and Globalization|place=Indiana|publisher=The Global South|pages=167\u2013182|date=2010}}</ref> The debate between quality and originality versus fame and fortune is a constant theme in ''Empire of Dreams''. The work closes with a quotation from an anonymous poem of [[Medieval Spanish literature]], a line from \"El Conde Arnaldos\": \"I only sing my song/to whomever follows me\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Braschi, Giannina|title=Empire of Dreams|publisher=AmazonCrossing|place=Seattle|page=197|ISBN=9781611090659|date=2011}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nGiannina Braschi credits T.S. Eliot's \"[[The Waste Land]]\" as the single most influential English-language poem to inform the rhythmic shifts and the inspiration from which she creates a chorus of anonymous voices to capture the collective conscience of the masses.<ref>{{cite interview|last=Braschi|first=Giannina|interviewer=Rathke, Eric J.|title=52 Weeks / 52 Interviews: Week 34: Giannina Braschi|quote=\"I've studied music all my life. I've sung songs in foreign languages and learned those languages through those songs. I memorized [[T.S. Eliot]]'s The Waste Land from tapes before I (mis)spoke English and discovered in Eliot's dramatic shifts my own music\u2014the anonymity of the voices that come from no where\u2014the Greek chorus that captures the conscience of the people.\"|url=http://monkeybicycle.net/52-weeks-52-interviews-week-34-giannina-braschi/|location=London|date=2014}}</ref> Feminist scholar and poet [[Alicia Ostriker]] notes in the introduction to ''Empire of Dreams'' that the poet's voice sounds decidedly \"[[macho]]\" and yet it can be theoretically \"paired with [[Luisa Valenzuela]], [[Clarice Lispector]], [[Luce Irigaray]], [[Helene Cixous]], and [[Marguerite Duras]], and obviously she owes a great deal to Gertrude Stein\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Ostriker|first=Alicia|title=Empire of Dreams|place=New Haven, CT|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=x-xxi|date=1994}}</ref> \n\nBraschi has published scholarly articles on Spanish-language poetry by [[Cervantes]], [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]], [[Antonio Machado]], [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]], and [[C\u00e9sar Vallejo]]; and a book on [[Gustavo Adolfo B\u00e9cquer]]. She quotes from their work throughout her book.<ref>{{cite web|title=NGO News|url=http://ngonewsbd.com/modern-language-association-convention-2013|quote=\"On the scholarly front, she published a book on the Spanish Romantic poet B\u00e9cquer and essays on classics by Cervantes, Garcilaso, Lorca, Machado, and Vallejo.\"|date=January 2013}}</ref> In an interview with NBC Latino, Braschi identified her favorite poet as C\u00e9sar Vallejo: \"Vallejo is a jack-in-the-box who performs the movement of my spirit. No matter how much you push him down into the box, the poet always bounces back to affirm his love for life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbclatino.com/2013/04/27/8-poets-disclose-their-favorite-lines-of-poetry/|title=8 Latino Poets Disclose Their Favorite Lines of Poetry|publisher=NBC Latino|quote=\"Nuyorican spoken word poet and author Giannina Braschi's favorite line from a poem is by C\u00e9sar Vallejo: I want to live always, even on my belly/because, as I was saying and I say it again/so much life and never! And so many years/and always, lots of always, always, always!\" (Translation by Tess O'Dwyer) \"Vallejo is a jack-in-the-box who performs the movement of my spirit,\" says Braschi. \"No matter how much you push him down into the box, the poet always bounces back to affirm his love for life.\"|date=2013}}</ref>\n\n==Giannina Braschi==\n{{Main|Giannina Braschi}}\n\nGiannina Braschi, a [[National Endowment for the Arts]] fellow, is considered an influential and revolutionary voice in contemporary [[Latin American literature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi|title=Giannina Braschi|work=National Book Festival|publisher=Library of Congress|year=2012|quote='Braschi, one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Giannina Braschi: Book Fest 12|publisher=Library of Congress|date=September 2012|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=5804|quote='Braschi, a poet, essayist and novelist often described as cutting-edge, influential and even revolutionary'|work=National Book Festival Transcript and Webcast|location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Publishing Perspectives|title=#BEA11: Books on Display, the Amazon Publishing Booth|first=Hannah|last=Johnson|date=May 26, 2011|url=http://publishingperspectives.com/2011/05/bea-books-amazon-publishing-booth|quote='Braschi is Puerto Rico's most influential and versatile writer of poetry, fiction, and essays'}}</ref> She is also the author of the [[Spanglish]] novel ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'', and the [[postcolonial]] novel ''[[United States of Banana]]'' (2011). Her collective work explores the politics of empire and independence, while capturing the trials and tribulations of the Latin American immigrant in the United States.<ref name=\"Jacobson1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Matthew Frye|title=American Studies Association President\u2019s Overview: 2012 ASA Convention Archives|publisher=ASA|date=September 15, 2012|url=http://asa.press.jhu.edu/program12/ASA_program.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Jacobson2\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Matthew Frye|date=March 15, 2013|url=http://www.theasa.net/from_the_editors/item/reflections_on_the_american_studies_association_meeting_san_juan_puerto_ric/|title=American Studies Association News From the Editors: Reflections on the Annual Meeting|access-date=2015-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222102239/http://www.theasa.net/from_the_editors/item/reflections_on_the_american_studies_association_meeting_san_juan_puerto_ric/#|archive-date=2015-12-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> She has won awards and grants from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], [[New York Foundation for the Arts]], [[PEN American Center]], [[Ford Foundation]], InterAmericas, Danforth Scholarship, Reed Foundation, El Diario, Rutgers University, and Puerto Rican Institute for Culture. With the publication of ''United States of Banana'', ''CARAS'' Magazine named Braschi one of the most influential Puerto Ricans in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=de la Torre|first= Patricia|title=CARAS 2012: Los grandes protagonistas de Puerto Rico|publisher=TELEVISA|date=December 2012 \u2013 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Literature|Poetry}}\n* [[Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]]\n* [[Experimental theater]]\n* [[Postmodern]]\n* [[Pastoral]]\n* [[Nuyorican Movement]]\n* [[McOndo]]\n* [[Puerto Rican literature]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Augenbraum, Harold and Stavans, Ilan (eds.). ''Lengua Fresca: Latinos Writing on the Edge'', Mariner Press, 2006.\n* Barnstone, Willis. ''Literature of Asia, Africa, and Latin America: From Antiquity to the Present'', Prentice Hall, 1999.\n* Barnstone, Willis, ''Literatures of Latin America'', Prentice Hall, p.&nbsp;460, 1991.\n* Bidaseca, Karina. \"Written in racialized bodies. Language, memory and (Post) colonial genealogies of femicide in Latin America.\" ''Journal of Latin American Communication Research'' 3.2 (2014): 135-161.\n* Castillo, Debra. ''ReDreaming America: Toward a Bilingual Culture'', State University of New York, 2005.\n*  Carrion, Maria Mercedes. \"Geography, (M)Other Tongues and the Role of Translation in Giannina Braschi's El imperio de los sue\u00f1os\", ''Studies in 20th Century Literature'', 20:1 (1996), 167-192\n* Cruz-Malav\u00e9, Arnaldo. \"Colonial figures in motion: globalization and translocality in contemporary Puerto Rican Literature in the United States.\" ''Centro 14'' (2002): 4-25.\n* Cruz-Malav\u00e9, Arnaldo Manuel. \"Under the Skirt of Liberty: Giannina Braschi Rewrites Empire.\" ''American Quarterly'' 66.3 (2014): 801-818.\n* Daniele, Daniela. Review of ''United States of Banana'', ''The Evergreen Review'', Issue #128, New York, November 2011.\n* Echeverr\u00eda, Miriam Balboa. \"Mirada y marejada en\" El imperio de los sue\u00f1os\" de Giannina Braschi.\" ''Confluencia'' (2002): 98-103.\n* Garrigos, Cristina. Review of ''United States of Banana'', ''The Evergreen Review'', Issue #128, New York, November 2011.\n* Gonzalez, Christopher Thomas. \"Hospitable Imaginations: Contemporary Latino/a Literature and the Pursuit of a Readership\", doctoral dissertation, Ohio State University, 2012.\n* Gray D\u00edaz, N., \"Performing Soledad: the Demythification of Identity in Giannina Braschi's ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'', ''Romance Notes'', 37:3 (1997), 331-338.\n* Goldstein, David and Thacker, Audrey (eds.), ''Complicating Constructions'', University of Washington Press, Seattle, 2007.\n* Gonzalez, Madelena. \"''United States of Banana'' (2011), ''Elizabeth Costello'' (2003) and ''Fury'' (2001): Portrait of the Writer as the 'Bad Subject' of Globalisation\", ''\u00c9tudes britanniques contemporaines'', Volume 46, July 2014.\n* Gonzalez, Madelena and Laplace-Claverie, Helene. ''Minority Theater on the Global Stage: Challenging Paradigms From the Margins'', Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2012. \"Puerto Rico's premier poet and novelist.\"\n* Haydee Rivera, Carmen. \"El poder de la palabra y la experiencia transnacional: una entrevista con Giannina Braschi,\" Op-Cit: ''Revista del Centro de Investigaciones Hist\u00f3ricas'', Puerto Rico, 2013.\n* Haydee Rivera, Carmen. \"Embracing alternate discourses on migration: Giannina Braschi's and Luisita L\u00f3pez Torregrosa's multi-dimensional literary schemes,\" ''Umbral'', University of Puerto Rico, April 2014.\n* Horno-Delgado, Asunci\u00f3n. \"Imperiosa y Anti-imperial: Giannina Braschi,\" ''Hispanic Poetry Review: HPR'' 4.7-10 (2002): 37.\n* Gonzalez, Christopher. \"Permissible Narratives: The Promise of Latino/o Literature,\" The Ohio State University Press, 2017. \n* Gonzales, Madelena and Laplace-Claverie, Helene, \"Minority Theatre on the Global Stage: Challenging Paradigms from the Margins,\" ''Cambridge Scholars'', Newcastle, England, 2012.\n* Kuebler, Carolyn, \"Empire of Dreams Review,\" ''Review of Contemporary Fiction'', vol 15, no. 1, Spring 1995.\n* Loustau, Laura. \"Nomadismos ling\u00fc\u00edsticos y culturales en Yo-Yo Boing! de Giannina Braschi\", ''Revista Iberoamericana'', volume 71:211, 437-448, 2005\n* Loustau, Laura. ''Cuerpos errantes: literatura Latina y latinoamericana en Estados Unidos'', Viterbo Editora, Buenos Aires, Argentina, 2002.\n* Loustau, Laura Rosa. ''Cuerpos y textos en tr\u00e1nsito: un acercamiento a la literatura Latina y latinoamericana en Estados Unidos''. University of California, Berkeley, 2000.\n* Marting, Diane E. \"New/Nueva York in Giannina Braschi's 'Poetic Egg': Fragile Identity, Postmodernism, and Globalization\", ''The Global South'', volume 4:1., 2010.\n* Morris, Barbara. \"Paradoxes of Postmodernism in Giannina Braschi's ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os''.\" Conflictos Culturales en la Literatura Contempor\u00e1nea. 17 ensayos y una discusi\u00f3n: 44-53.\n* Ostriker, Alicia. \"Introduction to ''Empire of Dreams'',\" Yale University Press, New Haven, 1994.\n* Perisic, Alexandra. \"Precarious Crossings: Immigration, Neoliberalism, and the Atlantic, The Ohio State University Press, 2019.\n* Popovich Ljudmila, Mila. \"Metafictions, Migrations, Metalives: Narrative Innovations and Migrant Women's Aesthetics in Giannina Braschi and Etel Adnan,\" ''International Journal of the Humanities'', 117\u2013128, 2010.\n* Sommer, Doris, Introduction to ''Yo-Yo Boing!'', Latin American Review Press, Pittsburgh, 1998.\n* Ramos, Francisco Jos\u00e9. ''Postfacio. El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'', Anthropos Editorial del Hombre, (1988): 233-253.\n* Riofrio, John. \"Falling for debt: Giannina Braschi, the Latinx avant-garde, and financial terrorism in the United States of Banana,\" Latino Studies, January 2020.  \n* Remeseria, Claudio. \"[http://nbclatino.com/2013/08/25/summer-reads-brilliant-takes-on-nuyoricans-random-murder-and-narco-literatura/ Summer reads: brilliant takes on Nuyoricans, random murder and narco-literatura],\" NBC Latino, August 2013.\n* Rivera Monclova, Marta S. \"Discrimination, evasion, and livability in four New York Puerto Rican narratives\". Doctoral dissertation, Tufts University, 2010.\n* Rodriguez Matos, Jaime, \"Unmothered Americas: Poetry and Universality\". Commons Digitalis at Columbia University Dissertation, 2005.\n* Waldron, John V. \"Killing Colonialism's Ghosts in McOndo: Mayra Santos Febres and Giannina Braschi,''Cuaderno Internacional de Estudios Human\u00edsticos y Literatura'', 2011.\n* Zimmerman, Marc. ''Defending Their Own in the Cold: The Cultural Turns of U.S. Puerto Ricans'', University of Illinois, Chicago, 2011.\n\n==External links==\n* Under the Skirt of Liberty, http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/american_quarterly/v066/66.3.cruz-malave.pdf\n* [http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-300-05795-9 ''Empire of Dreams Review''], ''Publishers Weekly'', 1994.\n* ''The Evergreen Review'', featuring [https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121638/http://www.evergreenreview.com/128/review_us_of_banana.shtml reviews of \"United States of Banana\"] by Cristina Garrigos and Daniela Daniele and videos of Giannina Braschi, November 2011.\n* [[Library of Congress]] Archives, Washington DC, September 24, 2012. [[National Book Festival]] ([https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=5804 Transcript and Webcast: Giannina Braschi])\n\n[[Category:Epic poems in Spanish]]\n[[Category:1988 books]]\n[[Category:Empire State Building in fiction]]\n[[Category:American poetry collections]]\n[[Category:Metafictional works]]\n[[Category:Postmodern literature]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican culture in the United States]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican plays]]\n[[Category:New York City in fiction]]\n[[Category:Postcolonial literature]]\n[[Category:Multiculturalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Books about democracy]]\n[[Category:Books about capitalism]]\n[[Category:Postmodern theatre]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican literature]]\n[[Category:Literature by Hispanic and Latino American women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Epic poetry book by Giannina Braschi}}\n{{Italic title}}\n'''''Empire of Dreams''''' ({{lang-es|El imperio de los sue\u00f1os}}, 1988) is a [[postmodern]] poetry epic by Puerto Rican author [[Giannina Braschi]], who is considered \"one of the most [[revolutionary]] voices in [[Latin American literature]] today\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi|title=Giannina Braschi|work=National Book Festival|publisher=Library of Congress|year=2012|quote=\"Braschi, one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Modern Language Association Presents Giannina Braschi|quote =\"Considered one of the most revolutionary Latin American poets writing today, Giannina Braschi, author of the epic prose poem 'Empire of Dreams'.\"|url=http://circumferencemag.org/?event=modern-language-association-presents-giannina-braschi|website=Circumference Magazine: Poetry in Translation, Academy of American Poets|date =January 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=World Literature in Translation: Giannina Braschi's Empire of Dreams|url=http://yalepress.yale.edu/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959&printer=y|website=Yale University Press|quote=\"Braschi's book is a modern classic, informed with all of the major concerns of our contemporary culture.\"|date=August 1994|access-date=2015-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091257/http://yalepress.yale.edu/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959&printer=y|archive-date=2015-05-18|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=PEN: Free Expression/Literature|url=https://www.pen.org/giannina-braschi|website=PEN American Center|quote=\"Giannina Braschi, one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today, wrote the postmodern poetry classic EMPIRE OF DREAMS.\"|date=November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=D'Amore|author2=Anna Maria|title='Translating Contemporary Mexican Texts: Fidelity to Alterity'|quote=\"In the stakes of literary acclaim and respectability is Giannina Braschi, considered by many to be Puerto Rico's premier poet.\"|publisher=Berkeley Insights in Linguistics and Semiotics|place=New York|page=104|date=2009}}</ref> Her third collection of poetry in Spanish, it was published in 1988 in Spain to acclaim as ''El imperio de los sue\u00f1os.'' \n\nIt was later combined with her first two poetry collections, translated into English by Tess O'Dwyer, and the trilogy was published in 1994 as ''Empire of Dreams,'' the first volume of the [[Yale]] Library of World Literature in Translation.<ref>{{Citation|last=Barnstone|first1=Willis|title=Literature of Asia, Africa, and Latin America: From Antiquity to the Present|quote=\"Empire of Dreams is an epic length sequence of poems published to acclaim\".../\"brightest new voice in her generation in the Spanish language.\"|place=Saddle River, NJ|publisher=Prentice Hall|page=1954|date=1994}}</ref> Composed from 1980 to 1986, this trilogy represents the first major phase of Braschi's [[Work of art|oeuvre]]: poetry written entirely in classical and modern Spanish.\n\nThe trilogy is a hybrid of genres: [[prose poetry]], [[drama]], [[musical theater]], [[manifesto]], [[gossip]], [[autobiography]], [[diary]], [[literary theory]], and [[antinovel]]. The central axis of this [[epic poem]] is the Latin American [[immigrant]]'s optimistic new life in the \"[[Big Apple]]\" (New York City), which is dramatized by Braschi as the epicenter of the [[American Dream]]. Social and linguistic references to Latin American cities and neighborhoods also abound, such as \"the Latin American Quarter in Paris, the ''barrio chino barcelon\u00e9s'', the ''zaguanes'' of Borges's Buenos Aires, and the colonial houses in Old San Juan\".<ref>{{cite journal|authorlink=Carrion, Maria Mercedes|title='Geography, (M)Other Tongues and the Role of Translation in Giannina Braschi's El imperio de los sue\u00f1os'|quote= \"the Latin American Quarter in Paris, the ''barrio chino barcelon\u00e9s'', the ''zaguanes'' of Borges's Buenos Aires, and the colonial houses in Old San Juan\".|journal=Studies in 20th Century Literature|volume=20|pages=167\u2013192|date=1996}}</ref>\n\n==Subject, structure, and themes==\n''Empire of Dreams'' deals with issues of artistic creation, [[immigration]], commercialism, [[capitalism]], [[identity crisis]], sexual and gender ambiguity, and [[revolution]]. The narrator journeys through a \"phantasmagoria of internal and external trials in order to experience the center\u2014of political power, of meaning, of feeling, and of personal identity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yalebooks.com/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959|title=Yale University Press Reviews|quote=\"New York City becomes the site of liberation for its marginal citizens, as the narrator is led through a seeming phantasmagoria of internal and external trials in order to experience the center\u2014of political power, of meaning, of feeling, and of personal identity.\"|date=August 1994|access-date=2015-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619011053/http://www.yalebooks.com/reviews.asp?isbn=9780300057959|archive-date=2015-06-19|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe work has been compared structurally to the [[Chinese boxes|Chinese box]] and the [[Matryoshka doll]]. It contains six books.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title= Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Literature|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Hispanic-American Literature|volume=5|pages=429|publisher=Infobase Learning|date=August 31, 2008|isbn =9781438140605}}</ref>\n\nPart one, \"Assault on Time\", is a sequence of meditative prose poems on the subject of love lost and the ineptitude of language and grammar to communicate emotions. It was published in 1980 as Braschi's first book of poetry in Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/2012/09/14/1ea74c24-f2e4-11e1-a612-3cfc842a6d89mar_story.html/|title=The Washington Post|quote=\"Giannina Braschi's first published work was a book of poetry, 'Asalto al tiempo'; since then she has had essays, a novella and more poetry published in Spanish. She went on to write the novel 'Yo-Yo Boing!' in [[Spanglish]]. Her new novel is her first in English 'United States of Banana.'|date=November 2012}}</ref> It begins with the breaking of silence: \"Behind the word is silence./Behind what sounds is the door\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Braschi, Giannina|title='Empire of Dreams' translated by Tess O'Dwyer|quote=\"Behind the word is silence./Behind what sounds is the door\"|publisher=Yale University Press|place=New Haven, CT|page=1|isbn=9780300057959|date=1994}}</ref> Letters take on a life of their own, roaming the streets of New York, and punctuation marks, such as [[Colon (punctuation)|colons]] and [[semicolon]]s, denote pivotal points in a relationship.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Literature|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Hispanic-American Literature|volume=5|pages=429|publisher=Infobase Learning|date=August 31, 2008|isbn =9781438140605}}</ref>\n\nPart two, \"Profane Comedy\", was also published first in Spanish, in 1985. It becomes \"loud\", as the poet pays homage to the evolution of poetry and performance, especially [[comedia dell'arte]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Ostriker|first=Alicia|title=Introduction to Empire of Dreams|quote=\"Profane Comedy is an homage to performance, especially comedia dell'arte.\"|place=New Haven, CT|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=x-xx1|date=1994}}</ref> \"Profane Comedy\" is composed of four books of poetry, each with humorous gusto and a flair for the grotesque: 1. \"Book of Clowns and Buffoons\", 2. \"Poems of the World; or The Book of Wisdom\", 3. \"Pastoral; or, The Inquisition of Memories\", and 4. \"Song of Nothingness\". Throughout, Braschi intermingles television [[jingles]] and pop songs by such singers as [[The Beatles]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] with poems of the [[Spanish Golden Age]]. References include [[Luis de Le\u00f3n]], [[Miguel de Cervantes]], [[Lope de Vega]], [[Luis de G\u00f3ngora]], [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso de la Vega]], and [[Francisco Quevedo]], while cameo appearances are made by poets, painters, philosophers, and composers, such as: [[C\u00e9sar Vallejo]], [[Rimbaud]], [[Goethe]], [[Nietzsche]], [[Shakespeare]], [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder|Breughal]], [[Beethoven]], [[Van Gogh]], and [[Picasso]], among others. She liberally quotes from classical poets, transformed by her use of the \"sampling technique of rap music\" and [[hip hop]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Ostriker|first=Alicia|title=Introduction to ''Empire of Dreams''|place=New Haven, CT|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=x-xx1|date=1994}}</ref> Though Braschi writes with a strong literary tradition behind her and from an erudite standpoint, \"she imbues her text with jollity and a brilliant energy\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Kuebler|first=Caroline|title=\"Empire of Dreams\" Review|quote=\"Braschi writes with a strong poetic tradition behind her, and from her erudite standpoint she forges an odd mixture of poetry, prose, drama, and a little of what could be considered music. She imbues her text with jollity and a brilliant energy that stretches its audience from lovers of modernism to seekers of a broadened artistry of language.\"|publisher=Review of Contemporary Fiction|place=Dalkey Archives, Champaign, Il|date=August 1994}}</ref> \n\nThe text unfolds through a series of violent and [[surrealism|surreal]]<ref>{{Citation|last=Barnstone|first1= Willis|title=Literature of Latin America|quote=\"Braschi is a Spanish Arthur Rimbaud reinventing surrealism, creating a modern classic\"|place=Princeton|publisher=Prentice Hall|page=460|date=2002}}</ref> theatrical scenes performed by clowns, buffoons, shepherds, lead soldiers, magicians, madmen, witches, and fortune tellers. These gender-bending immigrant characters attack and occupy the American mainstream, including business centers and tourist attractions.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Cruz Malave, Arnaldo|title=Under the Skirt of Liberty: Giannina Braschi Rewrites Empire|journal=American Quarterly|volume=66.3|pages=801\u2013818|date=2015}}</ref> In a climactic episode of \"[[Pastoral]]; or, the [[Inquisition]] of Memories\", shepherds cause traffic jams on [[Fifth Avenue|5th Avenue]] during the [[Puerto Rican Day Parade]], ring the bells of [[St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)|St. Patrick's Cathedral]], and take over the observation deck of the [[Empire State Building]]. There they dance and sing: \"Now we do whatever we please, whatever we please, whatever we damn well please\".\n\nPart three, \"Intimate Diary of Solitude,\" is a lighthearted [[antinovel]] that mocks the [[Latin American Boom]] and [[dictator novel]]s. The composition is a mix-mash of [[flash fiction]], pop songs, [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]], [[Advertising|commercials]], diary excerpts, political and literary [[manifestos]], and performance art, closing with a philosophical treatise on the writer's role in the modern age. The heroine Mariquita Samper, a [[Macy's]] make-up artist who dreams of being a star, calls for a revolution of \"poetic eggs\" and shoots the [[narrator]] of Latin American Boom novels (such as ''[[One Hundred Years of Solitude]]''), who keeps rewriting her own diary in order to turn it into a bestseller.<ref>{{Citation|last=Marting|first1=Diane|title= New/Nueva York in Giannina Braschi's 'Poetic Egg': Fragile Identity, Postmodernism, and Globalization|place=Indiana|publisher=The Global South|pages=167\u2013182|date=2010}}</ref> The debate between quality and originality versus fame and fortune is a constant theme in ''Empire of Dreams''. The work closes with a quotation from an anonymous poem of [[Medieval Spanish literature]], a line from \"El Conde Arnaldos\": \"I only sing my song/to whomever follows me\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Braschi, Giannina|title=Empire of Dreams|publisher=AmazonCrossing|place=Seattle|page=197|ISBN=9781611090659|date=2011}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nGiannina Braschi credits T.S. Eliot's \"[[The Waste Land]]\" as the single most influential English-language poem to inform the rhythmic shifts and the inspiration from which she creates a chorus of anonymous voices to capture the collective conscience of the masses.<ref>{{cite interview|last=Braschi|first=Giannina|interviewer=Rathke, Eric J.|title=52 Weeks / 52 Interviews: Week 34: Giannina Braschi|quote=\"I've studied music all my life. I've sung songs in foreign languages and learned those languages through those songs. I memorized [[T.S. Eliot]]'s The Waste Land from tapes before I (mis)spoke English and discovered in Eliot's dramatic shifts my own music\u2014the anonymity of the voices that come from no where\u2014the Greek chorus that captures the conscience of the people.\"|url=http://monkeybicycle.net/52-weeks-52-interviews-week-34-giannina-braschi/|location=London|date=2014}}</ref> Feminist scholar and poet [[Alicia Ostriker]] notes in the introduction to ''Empire of Dreams'' that the poet's voice sounds decidedly \"[[macho]]\" and yet it can be theoretically \"paired with [[Luisa Valenzuela]], [[Clarice Lispector]], [[Luce Irigaray]], [[Helene Cixous]], and [[Marguerite Duras]], and obviously she owes a great deal to Gertrude Stein\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Ostriker|first=Alicia|title=Empire of Dreams|place=New Haven, CT|publisher=Yale University Press|pages=x-xxi|date=1994}}</ref> \n\nBraschi has published scholarly articles on Spanish-language poetry by [[Cervantes]], [[Garcilaso de la Vega (poet)|Garcilaso]], [[Antonio Machado]], [[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]], and [[C\u00e9sar Vallejo]]; and a book on [[Gustavo Adolfo B\u00e9cquer]]. She quotes from their work throughout her book.<ref>{{cite web|title=NGO News|url=http://ngonewsbd.com/modern-language-association-convention-2013|quote=\"On the scholarly front, she published a book on the Spanish Romantic poet B\u00e9cquer and essays on classics by Cervantes, Garcilaso, Lorca, Machado, and Vallejo.\"|date=January 2013}}</ref> In an interview with NBC Latino, Braschi identified her favorite poet as C\u00e9sar Vallejo: \"Vallejo is a jack-in-the-box who performs the movement of my spirit. No matter how much you push him down into the box, the poet always bounces back to affirm his love for life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbclatino.com/2013/04/27/8-poets-disclose-their-favorite-lines-of-poetry/|title=8 Latino Poets Disclose Their Favorite Lines of Poetry|publisher=NBC Latino|quote=\"Nuyorican spoken word poet and author Giannina Braschi's favorite line from a poem is by C\u00e9sar Vallejo: I want to live always, even on my belly/because, as I was saying and I say it again/so much life and never! And so many years/and always, lots of always, always, always!\" (Translation by Tess O'Dwyer) \"Vallejo is a jack-in-the-box who performs the movement of my spirit,\" says Braschi. \"No matter how much you push him down into the box, the poet always bounces back to affirm his love for life.\"|date=2013}}</ref>\n\n==Giannina Braschi==\n{{Main|Giannina Braschi}}\n\nGiannina Braschi, a [[National Endowment for the Arts]] fellow, is considered an influential and revolutionary voice in contemporary [[Latin American literature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/bookfest/author/giannina_braschi|title=Giannina Braschi|work=National Book Festival|publisher=Library of Congress|year=2012|quote='Braschi, one of the most revolutionary voices in Latin America today'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Giannina Braschi: Book Fest 12|publisher=Library of Congress|date=September 2012|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=5804|quote='Braschi, a poet, essayist and novelist often described as cutting-edge, influential and even revolutionary'|work=National Book Festival Transcript and Webcast|location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Publishing Perspectives|title=#BEA11: Books on Display, the Amazon Publishing Booth|first=Hannah|last=Johnson|date=May 26, 2011|url=http://publishingperspectives.com/2011/05/bea-books-amazon-publishing-booth|quote='Braschi is Puerto Rico's most influential and versatile writer of poetry, fiction, and essays'}}</ref> She is also the author of the [[Spanglish]] novel ''[[Yo-Yo Boing!]]'', and the [[postcolonial]] novel ''[[United States of Banana]]'' (2011). Her collective work explores the politics of empire and independence, while capturing the trials and tribulations of the Latin American immigrant in the United States.<ref name=\"Jacobson1\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Matthew Frye|title=American Studies Association President\u2019s Overview: 2012 ASA Convention Archives|publisher=ASA|date=September 15, 2012|url=http://asa.press.jhu.edu/program12/ASA_program.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Jacobson2\">{{Cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Matthew Frye|date=March 15, 2013|url=http://www.theasa.net/from_the_editors/item/reflections_on_the_american_studies_association_meeting_san_juan_puerto_ric/|title=American Studies Association News From the Editors: Reflections on the Annual Meeting|access-date=2015-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222102239/http://www.theasa.net/from_the_editors/item/reflections_on_the_american_studies_association_meeting_san_juan_puerto_ric/#|archive-date=2015-12-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> She has won awards and grants from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], [[New York Foundation for the Arts]], [[PEN American Center]], [[Ford Foundation]], InterAmericas, Danforth Scholarship, Reed Foundation, El Diario, Rutgers University, and Puerto Rican Institute for Culture. With the publication of ''United States of Banana'', ''CARAS'' Magazine named Braschi one of the most influential Puerto Ricans in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=de la Torre|first= Patricia|title=CARAS 2012: Los grandes protagonistas de Puerto Rico|publisher=TELEVISA|date=December 2012 \u2013 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Literature|Poetry}}\n* [[Multi-Ethnic Literature of the United States]]\n* [[Experimental theater]]\n* [[Postmodern]]\n* [[Pastoral]]\n* [[Nuyorican Movement]]\n* [[McOndo]]\n* [[Puerto Rican literature]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Augenbraum, Harold and Stavans, Ilan (eds.). ''Lengua Fresca: Latinos Writing on the Edge'', Mariner Press, 2006.\n* Barnstone, Willis. ''Literature of Asia, Africa, and Latin America: From Antiquity to the Present'', Prentice Hall, 1999.\n* Barnstone, Willis, ''Literatures of Latin America'', Prentice Hall, p.&nbsp;460, 1991.\n* Bidaseca, Karina. \"Written in racialized bodies. Language, memory and (Post) colonial genealogies of femicide in Latin America.\" ''Journal of Latin American Communication Research'' 3.2 (2014): 135-161.\n* Castillo, Debra. ''ReDreaming America: Toward a Bilingual Culture'', State University of New York, 2005.\n*  Carrion, Maria Mercedes. \"Geography, (M)Other Tongues and the Role of Translation in Giannina Braschi's El imperio de los sue\u00f1os\", ''Studies in 20th Century Literature'', 20:1 (1996), 167-192\n* Cruz-Malav\u00e9, Arnaldo. \"Colonial figures in motion: globalization and translocality in contemporary Puerto Rican Literature in the United States.\" ''Centro 14'' (2002): 4-25.\n* Cruz-Malav\u00e9, Arnaldo Manuel. \"Under the Skirt of Liberty: Giannina Braschi Rewrites Empire.\" ''American Quarterly'' 66.3 (2014): 801-818.\n* Daniele, Daniela. Review of ''United States of Banana'', ''The Evergreen Review'', Issue #128, New York, November 2011.\n* Echeverr\u00eda, Miriam Balboa. \"Mirada y marejada en\" El imperio de los sue\u00f1os\" de Giannina Braschi.\" ''Confluencia'' (2002): 98-103.\n* Garrigos, Cristina. Review of ''United States of Banana'', ''The Evergreen Review'', Issue #128, New York, November 2011.\n* Gonzalez, Christopher Thomas. \"Hospitable Imaginations: Cont