{"title_page": "African immigration to Israel", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Plitim1.jpg|thumb|African migrants demonstrating in Tel Aviv]]\n'''African immigration to Israel''' is the phenomenon of migrants from different countries in Africa entering Israel illegally or claiming to be asylum-seekers.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ron Friedman |date=2 February 2010 |url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel/Human-rights-groups-slam-state-on-refugee-statements |title=Human rights groups slam state on refugee statements |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Attila Somfalvi |date=13 December 2010 |url=http://www.shebacss.com/en/media-center-59784.html |title=Israel deporting Sudanese infiltrators |newspaper=[[Yedioth Ahronoth]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716052836/http://www.shebacss.com/en/media-center-59784.html |archivedate=16 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Yehuda Bauer |authorlink=Yehuda Bauer |date=28 December 2010 |url=http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Op-Ed-Contributors/Why-should-we-care |title=Why should we care? |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |accessdate=16 September 2014 |quote=Today, the national policy is to stop the infiltration of Africans from Egypt as drastically as possible.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Dana Weiler-Polak |date=22 November 2010 |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/eli-yishai-infiltrators-pose-existential-threat-to-israel-1.326075 |title=Eli Yishai: Infiltrators pose existential threat to Israel |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=14 December 2010 |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3998642,00.html |title=Israel flying Sudanese infiltrators back to Africa |publisher=[[Ynetnews]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=19 July 2010 |url=http://www.mfa.gov.il/mfa/pressroom/2010/pages/israel_block_infiltrators_africa_19-jul-2010.aspx |title=Israel to take significant steps to block infiltrators from Africa |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Israel)]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=19 July 2010 |url=http://www.pmo.gov.il/PMOEng/Communication/Spokesman/2010/07/spokeafrica190710.htm |title=Israel to Take Significant Steps to Block Infiltrators from Africa |publisher=[[Prime Minister of Israel]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726032545/http://www.pmo.gov.il/PMOEng/Communication/Spokesman/2010/07/spokeafrica190710.htm |archivedate=26 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mops.gov.il/BPEng/MOPS+News/MinisterDicterVisitsAfricanRefugees_18_7_07.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805144435/http://www.mops.gov.il/BPEng/MOPS+News/MinisterDicterVisitsAfricanRefugees_18_7_07.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=The IDF is responsible for preventing infiltration through the border |publisher=[[Ministry of Public Security (Israel)]]}}</ref> This phenomenon began in the second half of the 2000s, when a large number of people from Africa entered Israel, mainly through the [[Borders of Israel#Border with Egypt|fenced border between Israel and Egypt]]. According to the data of the [[Ministry of Interior (Israel)|Israeli Interior Ministry]], 26,635 people arrived illegally in this way by July 2010,<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data 3\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02625.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05e2\u05dc \u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d5\u05db\u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea \u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=Data on crimes made by illegal immigrants and asylum seekers and of crimes made against illegal immigrants and asylum seekers|date=11 October 2010 |page=3 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> and over 55,000 by January 2012.<ref>{{cite web |date=January 2012 |url=http://www.piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/%D7%A1%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%9D%20%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%AA%D7%99%202011.pdf |script-title=he:\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israeli foreign data |publisher=Israeli authority of population and immigration |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> In an attempt to curb the influx,<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">Butcher, Tim. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/1504945/Sharon-presses-for-fence-across-Sinai.html Sharon presses for fence across Sinai], ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 December 2005.</ref> Israel constructed the [[Egypt\u2013Israel barrier]], which was completed in December 2013.<ref name=\"algemeiner.com\">[http://www.algemeiner.com/2013/12/04/245-mile-1-6-billion-shekel-security-fence-between-israel-and-sinai-completed Israel Completes 245 Mile, NIS 1.6 Billion Security Fence Along Sinai Border with Egypt] Algemeiner, 4 December 2013 2:58 PM</ref>\n\nAs of January 2018, according to the Population and Immigration Authority (PIBA) there were around 30,000+ African refugees, migrants and asylum seekers in Israel, not including children born to parents in Israel.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.il/BlobFolder/reports/foreign_workers_in_israel_summary_2017/he/foreigners_in_Israel_data_2017_1.pdf|title=\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc|date=January 2018|website=Population and Immigration Authority|language=he|access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMost African migrants are regarded to be legitimate asylum seekers by human rights organizations,<ref>{{cite web |date=8 October 2012 |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/10/28/israel-asylum-seekers-blocked-border |title=Israel: Asylum Seekers Blocked at Border |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=10 January 2012 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/new-israeli-detention-law-violates-asylum-seekers-rights-2012-01-10 |title=Israel: New detention law violates rights of asylum-seekers |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> but the Israeli government says most of them are job seeking work-migrants.<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrants-reel-as-israeli-law-cuts-into-their-salaries/ African migrants reel as Israeli law cuts into their salaries]</ref>\n\nMany of the migrants seek asylum status under the United Nations [[Convention relating to the Status of Refugees]]. Citizens of [[Eritrea]] and [[Sudan]] cannot be forcibly deported from Israel. Under international law, Eritrea citizens (who, since 2009, form the majority of the undocumented workers in Israel) cannot be deported due to the opinion of the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] (UNHCR) that Eritrea has a difficult internal situation and a forced recruitment and therefore the Eritrean immigrants are defined as a \"temporary humanitarian protection group\". Israeli authorities have stated that they could not deport Sudanese directly back to Sudan because Israel has no diplomatic ties to Sudan.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2014/09/09/make-their-lives-miserable/israels-coercion-eritrean-and-sudanese-asylum-seekers|title=Make Their Lives Miserable|date=9 September 2014|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=21 January 2018}}</ref> Accordingly, the Israeli authorities grant temporary residence through \"conditional release permits\" which must be renewed every one to four months, depending on the discretion of the individual immigration official.<ref name=\":1\" /> Various authorities in Israel estimate that 80\u201390% of the undocumented workers live primarily in two centers: more than 60% in [[Tel Aviv]] and more than 20% [[Eilat]], with a few in [[Ashdod]], [[Jerusalem]] and [[Arad, Israel|Arad]].<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data 3\" />\n\n== Legal status ==\nAccording to the government, the majority of the migrants are seeking economic opportunity. This is not the case among Israel's allies such as the United States, where the vast majority of Eritrean and Sudanese applicants are accepted as refugees. Once in Israel, African migrants have sought refugee status for fleeing forced, open-ended conscription in Eritrea or ethnic cleansing in the Darfur region of Sudan, but the government of Israel maintains that these areas merely have a poor human rights record, which does not automatically entitle one to asylum. To qualify, applicants must establish that they face the risk of personal harm or persecution if they return to their country. The [[Ministry of Interior (Israel)|Interior Ministry]] has failed to review the vast majority of asylum requests.<ref name=\"hope\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-african-migrants-in-israel-have-little-hope-2014jan07-story.html |title=African migrants in Israel have little hope |author=David Mac Dougall and Josef Federman |publisher=Associated Press |date=7 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nMost migrants request refugee status after arriving in Israel, in accordance with the United Nations's [[Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees]]. Israel does not review the status of the individual immigrants originating from Eritrea or Sudan, who constitute about 83% of the total people coming to Israel across the Egyptian border,<ref>{{cite web |date=April 2012 |url=http://www.piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dc%202012.pdf|script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israeli foreign data |publisher=Israel Population and Immigration Authority |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> and instead automatically grants them a [[Israeli policy for Sudanese and_Eritrean refugees|\"temporary protection group\"]] status. This status allows these people to have temporary residence right within Israel, which must be renew every 3 months; usually this also means that they would be eligible for a [[work permit]] in Israel. In the past Israel also granted an automatic \"temporary protection group\" status to all citizens of the [[Ivory Coast]] and [[South Sudan]], although since then the validity of this status has expired. Regarding the other asylum requests filed by citizens of other countries and examined individually, the Interior Ministry stated that only a fraction of them were actually eligible for refugee status.<ref>{{cite news| author=Zahava Galeon |date=12 November 2010 |url=http://www.israelhayom.co.il/site/newsletter_opinion.php?id=4936&newsletter=12.11.2010 |script-title=he:\u05de\u05e1\u05d9\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd \u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Agitators against refugees |newspaper=[[Israel HaYom]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Israeli government originally tolerated the new arrivals from Africa. It allowed their entry and many migrants found menial jobs in hotels and restaurants. But after their numbers swelled, concerns were raised.<ref name=\"hope\"/> In the second half of the 2000s decade, there was a significant increase in the number of undocumented workers from Africa to Israel who crossed the Egyptian border. In 2006 about 1,000 undocumented workers were detained; in 2007 about 5,000 were detained; in 2008 about 8,700 were detained; and in 2009 about 5,000 were detained.<ref>{{cite web |date=26 May 2010 |script-title=he:\u05d4\u05d8\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d2\u05d1\u05d5\u05dc \u05de\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Treatment infiltrators from the border with Egypt |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02524.pdf |publisher=Knesset Research and Information Center |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> In the first half of 2010 the migration rate even further increased in the first seven months when over 8,000 undocumented workers were caught.<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data\">{{cite web |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02625.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05e2\u05dc \u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d5\u05db\u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea \u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=Data on crimes made by illegal immigrants and asylum seekers and of crimes made against illegal immigrants and asylum seekers|date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The total number of undocumented workers is clearly greater than these figures, because many were not apprehended.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}} The early wave of undocumented workers came mainly from Sudan, while in 2009 the majority of the immigrants were from [[Eritrea]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\nIn early May 2010, it was estimated that 24,339 undocumented workers resided in Israel, of whom the number of Sudanese and Eritrean refugees who are not deportable under [[international law]] was 18,959: 5,649 Sudanese and 13,310 Eritreans. 16,766 of them received a special visa (\u05e1 2\u05d0 5) granted to illegal immigrants who are non-deportable [[asylum seekers]]. Officially, the visa allows them only to stay in the country, but in practice the state also allows the refugees to work and avoids imposing fines on the Israeli employers who employ them. This special visa requires renewal every three months.<ref>{{cite web |date=8 June 2010 |script-title=he:\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05e0\u05d9\u05e6\u05d5\u05dc \u05dc\u05de\u05d8\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05de\u05d9\u05df \u05d5\u05e2\u05d1\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05e7\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d4\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Victims of exploitation for sexual purposes and slavery among the infiltrators and asylum seekers in Israel |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/doc.asp?doc=m02534&type=pdf |publisher=Knesset Research and Information Center |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The Israeli immigration police patrols the neighborhoods of south [[Tel Aviv]] regularly and arrests asylum seekers who do not carry a valid visa; the punishment can be one to three months in prison. \n\n141 immigrants, mostly from [[Ethiopia]], received [[refugee status]].\n\nAccording to the IDF's Operations Division in 2008, most of the countries from where the illegal immigrants came are (in descending order): [[Eritrea]], [[Sudan]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Ivory Coast]] and [[Nigeria]]. Most of the illegal immigrants (85%) were men.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |date=December 2009 |url=http://web.hevra.haifa.ac.il/~ch-strategy/images/publications/darfur_refugees.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d0\u05d5 \u05de\u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d9 \u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05d4 \u05de\u05de\u05d3\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 |language=he |trans-title=Refugees or migrant workers from African states |publisher=Research Center, National Defense College and Chaikin Chair in Geostrategy, University of Haifa |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814142203/http://web.hevra.haifa.ac.il/~ch-strategy/images/publications/darfur_refugees.pdf |archivedate=14 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMost migrants initially arrive in [[Egypt]], and then pay sums of up to two thousand dollars for [[Bedouin]] smugglers to transfer them to the border between Egypt and Israel. There have been cases of abuse against the female migrants committed by the Bedouin smugglers, including [[rape]], kidnapping for ransom, and murder. Another danger for the migrants includes the Egyptian army policy to shoot at them in order to prevent crossing the Egypt/Israel border.<ref>{{cite news |author=Liam Stack |date=13 November 2008|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2008/1113/p06s03-wome.html |title=Human Rights Watch faults Egypt's 'shoot-to-stop' policy |newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Amir Bohbot |date=2 October 2011 |url=http://news.walla.co.il/?w=/0/1865224 |script-title=he:\u05ea\u05d5\u05e4\u05e2\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d2\u05d1\u05d5\u05dc \u05d4\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05de\u05d9: \u05d4\u05e6\u05d1\u05d0 \u05d4\u05de\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d9\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d1\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=The southern border phenomenon: the Egyptian army shoots infiltrators |publisher=[[Walla!]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nTo contain the illegal entry of persons, construction of the [[Egypt\u2013Israel barrier]] commenced in 2012 and was completed in 2015. 9,570 citizens of various African countries entered Israel illegally in the first half of 2012, while only 34 did the same in the first six months of 2013, after construction of the main section of the barrier was completed.<ref>[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/169521#.UeXqBUB15DQ New Data Shows 99% Drop in Illegal Entry], Arutz Sheva. 2 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action 99.6% Drop in the Number of Infiltrators Entering Israel Due to Government Action] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930062343/http://netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action |date=30 September 2013 }}, Israeli Prime Minister official website. 1 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4402834,00.html Israel to trade arms for migrants with African countries], Ynetnews.com. 9 July 2013</ref> After the entire fence was completed, the number of migrant crossings had dropped to 16 in 2016.<ref>[http://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Israel-completes-heightened-Egypt-border-fence-478840 ISRAEL COMPLETES HEIGHTENED EGYPT BORDER FENCE]</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs of April 2012, 59,858 illegal immigrants who were never imprisoned in detention facilities have illegally enter into Israel (in August 2010 the number of the imprisoned was 1,900).<ref>{{cite web |date=April 2012 |url=http://piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dc%202012.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israel Foreign Data |publisher=Israel Population and Immigration Authority |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> Several thousands of them did not end up staying in the country.<ref>{{cite web |date=November 2011 |url=http://piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/nov2011.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israeli Foreign Data |publisher=Israel Population and Immigration Authority |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The Israeli department of immigration does not keep continuous supervision over their place of residence but, according to estimates based on data from the Israeli police, the local authorities and the aid organizations, approximately 34,000 illegal immigrants originated from [[Eritrea]], about 15,000 originated from [[Sudan]] and 10,000 originated from other countries. The Israeli [[Administration of Border Crossings, Population and Immigration]] does not keep detailed documentation regarding their place of residence, but according to estimates from 2011, which are based on data from the Israeli police, the local authorities and the NGOs, circa 15,000\u201317,000 illegal immigrants lived in [[Tel Aviv]] (mainly in southern Tel Aviv, though the number also includes illegal immigrants living in [[Bat Yam]] and [[Bnei Brak]]) and 4,000\u20138,000 living in [[Eilat]]. While the estimates in [[Ashdod]] range from 1,500 to 2,000 illegal immigrants, in [[Jerusalem]] range from 1,000 to 8,000 illegal immigrants, and in [[Arad, Israel|Arad]] range from 400 to 600 illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |date=25 May 2011 |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02844.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d5\u05db\u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=Crime of infiltrators and asylum seekers and against infiltrators and asylum seekers |publisher=Knesset Research and Information Center |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> As of 2017, only 39,274 of those who entered the country remain.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Criminal activity==\nIn December 2010, Police commissioner [[Dudi Cohen]] stated that despite a decline in [[robberies]] in the general population, there was a dramatic increase in this type of crime among the illegal immigrants. According to the research department of the Israel Police and Israel's foreign immigrants' crime is characterized by predominantly sectoral internal crime, in which a gun is not reported, and illegal immigrants generally have no interest in complaining to the police.<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data\" /> Due to an increase in criminal acts and the feeling of insecurity among the residents of southern Tel Aviv, the Israeli police established a new station near the New central bus station and the Shapira neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news |author=Avi Cohen |date=18 May 2012 |url=http://www.israelhayom.co.il/site/newsletter_article.php?id=17206&hp=1&newsletter=18.05.2012 |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05d7\u05d3 \u05d1\u05e8\u05d7\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea |language=he |trans-title=Fear in the streets  |newspaper=[[Israel HaYom]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The station includes approximately 100 police officers and is expected to accommodate about 150 police officers. According to the data of the Israeli Police, which was presented to the Knesset in March 2012, from 2007 there was a steady increase in the involvement in crime of the illegal immigrants, both due to the significant increase in their numbers and for various other reasons. In 2011, 1,200 [[criminal case]]s were opened against illegal immigrants from Africa, half of them in the Tel Aviv district. This is an increase of 54% in comparison to the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |author=Omri Efraim |date=19 March 2012 |script-title=he:\u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05d8\u05e8\u05d4: \u05e2\u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc 23% \u05d1\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05ea \u05d4\u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Police: up 23% of crime is foreign |publisher=[[Ynet]] }} http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/1,7340,L-4204802,00.html</ref>\n\nMassive protests supporting the immigrants and their remaining in Israel have taken place<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/amphtml/world/africa/thousands-of-africans-protest-israeli-deportation-plan/2018/03/24/cda24fea-2f91-11e8-8dc9-3b51e028b845_story.html|title=Thousands of Africans protest Israeli deportation plan|website=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5130004,00.html|title=20,000 asylum seekers, supporters, protest in Tel Aviv|date=25 February 2018|work=Ynetnews|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> simultaneous with other Israelis calling for their deportation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.mida.org.il/2017/03/22/south-tel-aviv-overtaken-illegal-immigrants-media-silent/|title=South Tel Aviv Being Overtaken by Illegal Immigrants, Media is Silent|date=22 March 2017|work=Mida|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5127607,00.html|title=Masses expected to attend Tel Aviv migrant solidarity rally|date=23 February 2018|work=Ynetnews|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Crime is a major factor for residents who call for the government to repatriate the migrants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4230650,00.html|title=3 Africans suspected of raping 15-year-old girl|date=17 May 2012|work=Ynetnews|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Examples include the murder of 68-year-old Esther Galili<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.maariv.co.il/news/law/Article-588893|title=\u05ea\u05d5\u05e9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05ea\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05d9\u05d1 \u05de\u05d0\u05e9\u05d9\u05de\u05d4 \u05d0\u05ea \u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05d8\u05e8\u05d4: \"\u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05e4\u05e9\u05e8 \u05dc\u05de\u05e0\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d0\u05ea \u05e8\u05e6\u05d7 \u05d0\u05de\u05d9\"|access-date=24 March 2018|language=he-IL}}</ref> who was beaten to death near her South Tel Aviv home in 2010 by a drunken Sudanese migrant. Her daughter Corine Galili is now an activist with the Residents of Southern Tel Aviv council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/155947|title=Murders by Illegals go Unreported|website=Israel National News|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Another example includes the rape of 83-year-old Ester Nahman by a 17-year-old Eritrean migrant in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.jpost.com/National-News/Charge-Eritrean-raped-and-beat-83-yr-old-for-hours|title=Charge: Eritrean raped and beat 83-yr-old for hours|work=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/170004|title=Eritrean Immigrant Held on Rape, Robbery of Disabled TA Woman|website=Israel National News|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> There has also been a concern of crimes committed by migrants against migrants including rape and murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrant-murdered-in-south-tel-aviv/amp/|title=African migrant murdered in south Tel Aviv {{!}} The Times of Israel|website=www.timesofisrael.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sudanese-woman-found-dead-in-south-tel-aviv/|title=Sudanese minor found dead in south Tel Aviv|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> According to David Filo, the police commander in charge of the district that includes south Tel Aviv, the local police station went from only four or five officers before the wave of immigrants, to more than 200 as of 2017 on duty around the clock due to the increase in crime. He stated that statistics indicate most of the crimes reported are between immigrants and include theft, drug sales and domestic violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.makorrishon.co.il/nrg/online/1/ART2/896/830.html|title=\u05de\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8 \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05df, ''\u05d0\u05dd \u05de\u05d9\u05e9\u05d4\u05d5 \u05de\u05e4\u05d7\u05d3 \u05dc\u05e6\u05d0\u05ea, \u05d9\u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05db\u05d5\u05d7 \u05e9\u05d9\u05d9\u05d2\u05e9 \u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d5''|work=NRG|access-date=24 March 2018|language=he}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli police reported experiencing difficulties dealing with criminal cases involving illegal African immigrants due to the lack of interpreters proficient in the [[Tigrinya language]] spoken in [[Eritrea]]. The Israeli legal system has encountered a similar problems.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 March 2012 |url=http://www.news1.co.il/uploadFiles/433315455913544.doc |script-title=he:\u05de\u05d3\u05d9\u05e0\u05ea \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc \u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d9\u05e0\u05d4 \u05e1\u05de\u05e8\u05d4\u05e8\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=State of Israel v. Byena Smarhart |publisher=[[Supreme Court of Israel]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn her ruling on the [[Holot]] \"open detention facility\", Israeli Supreme Court justice [[Edna Arbel]] stated that whereas studies that show the level of crime committed by infiltrators is lower than in society in general, the distress of residents of South Tel Aviv should not be underestimated.<ref>{{cite web |date=16 September 2013 |last1=Arbel|first1=Edna|title=Adam v. The Knesset|url=http://elyon1.court.gov.il/files_eng/12/460/071/b24/12071460.b24.pdf |publisher=[[Supreme Court of Israel]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Handling of asylum seekers==\n[[File:Holot detention center.jpg|thumb|The entrance to Holot immigration detention center, Negev desert, Israel.]]\nIn 2010, Israel began building a [[Israel\u2013Egypt barrier|barrier]] along sections of its border with Egypt to curb the influx of [[refugees]] from African countries. Construction was completed in January 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel completes bulk of Egypt border fence |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/02/us-israel-egypt-fence-idUSBRE9010EI20130102 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2 January 2013 |accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref> 230&nbsp;km of fence have been built.<ref>{{cite news |author=Herb Keinon |url=http://www.jpost.com/Defense/PM-tours-South-heralds-completion-of-border-fence |title=PM tours South, heralds completion of border fence |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=2 January 2013 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> While 9,570 citizens of various African countries entered Israel illegally in the first half of 2012, only 34 did the same in the first six months of 2013, after construction of the barrier was completed. It represents a decrease of over 99%.<ref>{{cite news |author=Maayana Miskin |date=2 July 2013 |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/169521 |title=New Data Shows 99% Drop in Illegal Entry |publisher=[[Arutz Sheva]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action |title=99.6% Drop in the Number of Infiltrators Entering Israel Due to Government Action |publisher=Benjamin Netanyahu Official Website |date=1 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930062343/http://netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action |archivedate=30 September 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIsrael also began deporting thousands of illegal immigrants residing in the country.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=3 June 2013 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/03/israel-plan-migrants-deport-east-africa |title=Israel planning to deport African migrants to 'east African country' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/middleeast/la-fg-israel-refugees-20130716,0,3081312.story |title=Israel begins deporting Eritrean refugees to troubled African homeland |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=15 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130717050104/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/middleeast/la-fg-israel-refugees-20130716%2C0%2C3081312.story |archivedate=17 July 2013  }}</ref> In 2017 Israel announced its intent to deport thousands of illegal immigrants by March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/israel-tells-african-migrants-asylum-seekers-to-leave-or-go-to-jail_us_5a4fc2c6e4b003133ec79e39|title=Israel Tells African Migrants, Asylum-Seekers To Leave Or Go To Jail|last=Cook|first=Jesselyn|date=5 January 2018|work=Huffington Post|access-date=14 January 2018|language=English}}</ref> African migrants are told to choose between returning to their home countries or being sent to third world countries, that are rumored to be Rwanda and Uganda.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/01/05/world/africa/ap-af-africa-israel-migrants.html|title=Rwanda, Uganda Deny Deal With Israel to Take Africa Migrants|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 January 2018|language=English|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Israeli Knesset announced that illegal immigrants who do not leave by March 2018 will be jailed until they leave Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://972mag.com/the-new-choice-for-asylum-seekers-deportation-or-prison/131534/|title=The new 'choice' for asylum seekers: Deportation or prison {{!}} +972 Magazine|website=972mag.com|language=English|date=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Knesset]] passed an \"anti-infiltration law.\"  Advocates like MK [[Michal Rozin]] visited Saharonim and said that migrants received adequate food and medical care and were not mistreated, but said that sending migrants there was inhumane. However, conditions for many refugees elsewhere in the region are worse.<ref name=\"prison\">{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/israeli-detention-center-africans-prison |title=Israeli: Detention center for Africans a 'prison' |author=Diaa Hadid |publisher=Associated Press |date=14 July 2013 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref> After the [[Supreme Court of Israel]] declared that the long-term custody of migrants in Sahronim was unconstitutional, the government opened [[Holot]], an open detention center, in December 2013. The 1,800 residents at [[Holot]] are allowed to leave but are required to sign in once a day and return for an evening curfew.<ref name=\"hope\"/><ref name=\"seder\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrants-in-israel-hold-passover-seder/ |title=African migrants in Israel hold Passover seder |author=Tia Goldenberg |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=11 April 2014 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref> Israeli courts temporarily cancelled the summonses of African migrants to the Holot facility, and froze others until appeals can be heard against them. Judges also criticized the summons process, saying there exist fundamental problems, including the failure to examine individual circumstances and the lack of hearings for illegal immigrants. The government stated that hearings were not necessary because ordering the migrants to travel to Holot does not violate their human rights.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.575211 |title=Judges nix summonses of illegal immigrants, slam Israel's detention policy |author=Ilan Lior |newspaper=Haaretz |date=20 February 2014 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2014, the High Court struck down the anti-infiltration law (under which the [[Holot]] facility operated) and ordered the state to close [[Holot]] within 90 days.<ref name=Holot1>{{cite news | author = Ilan Lior | title = High Court orders closure of detention facility for African asylum seekers | newspaper = [[Haaretz]] | date = 22 September 2014 | url = http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.617143}}</ref> The court addressed two measures: (1) whether to limit the detention of migrants, and (2) whether to close Holot. On both measures, the court sided with the petitioners (the [[Association for Civil Rights in Israel]], the [[Hotline for Refugees and Migrants]], ASSAF, [[Kav LaOved]], [[Physicians for Human Rights\u2013Israel]], and [[Amnesty International]]\u2013Israel).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/in-dramatic-ruling-supreme-court-rejects-israels-policies-on-illegal-migrants/ |title=In dramatic ruling, High Court rejects Israel's policies on illegal migrants |author=Marissa Newman |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=22 September 2014}}</ref> The ruling said that conditions at the facility were an \"unbearable violation of [their] basic rights, first and foremost the right to freedom and the right to dignity\".<ref name=Holot1/> Illegal migrants can no longer be detained for up to a year without trial, however detention continues within legal boundaries.<ref name=\"new law\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-ministers-mull-new-migrant-law/ |title=Netanyahu, ministers mull new migrant law |publisher=AFP |date=7 October 2014}}</ref> The detentions in Holot have continued, with illegal immigrants being detained for a year and then being prevented from living in Tel Aviv and Eilat upon their release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/26/middleeast/israel-migrant-release/index.html|title=Israel frees 1,200 migrants, bans them from Tel Aviv|author-link=Oren Liebermann|first=Oren |last=Liebermann|work=CNN|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> In November 2017, the Israeli government announced that it would be closing the Holot Detention Center within four months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5044929,00.html|title=Government approves closure of Holot facility within 4 months|date=19 November 2017|work=Ynetnews|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nA law passed in 2017 required that employers impose a 20 per cent deduction on the [[wages]] of workers who entered the country illegally from [[Egypt]]. The deducted money is deposited in a fund along with an employer paid [[Taxation in Israel|tax]] of 16 per cent. This money is accessible to workers only when they leave Israel.<ref>{{Cite web| title = African migrant families battle hunger in Israel| work = Middle East Monitor| accessdate = 8 November 2018| date = 8 November 2018| url = https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181108-african-migrant-families-battle-hunger-in-israel/}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Israel reached an agreement with the [[United Nations]] to expel around 16,000 African migrants to Western countries in exchange for granting temporary residency in Israel to the same number.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Israel-announces-it-reached-deal-with-UN-on-deportation-of-asylum-seekers-547703|title=Israel reaches deal with U.N. to resettle asylum seekers in Western states|work=Jerusalem Post|date=2 April 2018}}</ref> Shortly after, however, the deal was cancelled by the Israeli government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Netanyahu-completes-about-face-on-migrants-says-UNHRC-deal-is-cancelled-547777|title=Netanyahu completes about-face on migrants, says UNHCR deal is cancelled|work=Jerusalem Post|date=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aid organizations==\nIsrael has a number of organizations focused legal aid, including the [[Hotline for Refugees and Migrants]], ASSAF, [[Physicians for Human Rights-Israel]], [[African Refugees Development Center]] and [[Association for Civil Rights in Israel]].  The secular Jewish organization [[BINA Center for Jewish Identity and Hebrew Culture|Bina]], located in south Tel Aviv, has helped asylum seekers as well as Israeli citizens understand refugee rights, and has undertaken advocacy and educational activities including frequent trips for Israelis to visit the Holot Detention Center. Most of these organization are funded by the [[New Israel Fund]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Akiva Bigman |date=1 January 2014 |url=http://mida.org.il/2014/01/01/%D7%90%D7%A1%D7%98%D7%A8%D7%98%D7%92%D7%99%D7%99%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%93%D7%A2%D7%95%D7%95%D7%94-%D7%A9%D7%9C-%D7%94%D7%A7%D7%A8%D7%9F-%D7%94%D7%97%D7%93%D7%A9%D7%94-%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%A8%D7%90/ |script-title=he:\u05d0\u05e1\u05d8\u05e8\u05d8\u05d2\u05d9\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4'\u05d3\u05e2\u05d5\u05d5\u05d4' \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05d4\u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=The strategy 'Dawa' of the New Israel Fund |publisher=MIDA |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> Relief organizations have been involved in discussions held in Knesset committees on this issue and have submitted a petition against the measures the state has taken to put a halt to the phenomenon of immigration.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\nunitaf creates early-childhood programs for refugee and stateless children living in Israel <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/.premium-who-will-save-the-refugee-children-of-tel-aviv-1.5347117/|title=Who Will Save the Refugee Children of Tel Aviv?|date=5 April 2015|publisher=Haaretz}}</ref>; the President of the board is [[Aliza Olmert]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unitaf.org/a-word-from-aliza-olmert/|title=President of the Board at unitaf - unitaf|date=8 April 2020|publisher=unitaf.org}}</ref>\n\n==Response in Israel==\nIsrael was founded in the wake of the Holocaust and has provided refuge to Jews fleeing oppression around the world. On one hand, many Israelis feel Israel has a special responsibility to assist refugees in such dire conditions.<ref name=\"hope\"/><ref name=\"seder\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sabar|first=Galia|last2=Tsurkov|first2=Elizabeth|date=May 2015|title=Israel's Policies towards Asylum-Seekers:2012\u20132014|journal=Instituto Affari Internazionali|volume=20|pages=2\u201318|isbn=978-88-98650-44-6}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli reaction to African migrants has been mixed. In 2010, Israelis protested the construction of the Holot detention facility built to detain illegal immigrants, stating that its construction goes against Human Rights values. At the same time, residents of South Tel Aviv demonstrated against the presence of foreigners living in their communities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/thousands-in-tel-aviv-protest-plan-for-refugee-detention-facility-1.332737|title=Thousands in Tel Aviv Protest Plan for Refugee Detention Facility|last=Lior|first=Ilan|date=24 December 2010|work=Haaretz|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> In 2012, nearly 1,000 Israelis, mostly from neighborhoods in South Tel Aviv staged a protest against illegal immigrants, joined by Member of Knesset[[Miri Regev]], they asked the government for deportation and expulsion of migrants from Africa.  Regev stated  \"the Sudanese were a cancer in our body.\" This protest led to destruction of property and businesses owned by Sudanese and Eritrean people as well as violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/06/10/israel-amend-anti-infiltration-law|title=Israel: Amend 'Anti-Infiltration' Law|date=10 June 2012|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/demonstrators-attack-african-migrants-in-south-tel-aviv-1.432262|title=Demonstrators Attack African Migrants in South Tel Aviv|last=Lior|first=Ilan|date=24 May 2012|work=Haaretz|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> In 2015, an immigrant from Eritrea, Habtom Zarhum, was beaten to death by a mob after being misidentified as the perpetrator in a [[Beersheva bus station shooting|terrorist attack at the Beersheva bus station]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/1.681069|title=Two Dead, 11 Wounded in Shooting Attack in Southern Israel|last=Ben Zikri|first=Almog|date=19 October 2015|website=Haaretz|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany Israelis have continued to show their support over the years for the community. Refugee [[Passover Seder|Seders]] have been held each year during the Jewish holiday of [[Passover]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Activists-hold-Seder-for-African-asylum-seekers-at-Holot-facility-451436|title=CTIVISTS HOLD SEDER FOR AFRICAN ASYLUM-SEEKERS AT HOLOT FACILITY|last=Sharon|first=Jeremy|date=17 April 2016|work=Jerusalem Post|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> Support is also demonstrated through the work of non-profit organizations, including [http://www.kavlaoved.org.il/en/ Kav LaOved (Worker's Hotline]), [https://www.ardc-israel.org/ ARDC], [http://assaf.org.il/en/node/2 ASSAF]. In late 2017, early 2018, North American Jewish organizations joined with Israeli NGOs to decry Israel's decision to close Holot and deport asylum seekers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/North-American-Jewish-leaders-Please-dont-deport-Africans-533195|title=NORTH AMERICAN JEWISH LEADERS: PLEASE DON'T DEPORT AFRICANS|last=Eisenbud|first=Daniel|date=9 January 2018|work=Jerusalem Post|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli demographer [[Arnon Soffer]] claims that from a security perspective, the migrants may serve as informant or as operatives of terrorist organizations. Socially, he claims that they are contributing to congestion in the cities and a rise in [[crime]]. From the demographic perspective, he perceives them as a [[Demographic threat#Israel|demographic threat]] to the Jewish majority. According to Sofer, failing to stop the illegal immigration waves at an early stage will only lead to much larger waves in the future.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nIsraeli economic commentator [[Nehemiah Shtrasler]] estimated that illegal immigrants take the places of weaker manual workers, causing loss of jobs and a reduction in the wages. He also claimed that they burden the health care, welfare and education systems. \"We would never be able to raise the standard of living of the needy and reduce the gaps, if we keep on absorbing more and more destitute people.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=24 September 2010 |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/opinions/1.1222412 |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05d7\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d8\u05e8\u05e1\u05dc\u05e8 &#124; 40 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05d5\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Nehemiah Shtrasler &#124; 4- Infiltrators a day |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli MK [[Ya'akov Katz (politician born 1951)|Ya'akov Katz]], who headed the government committee on issue of illegal asylum seekers, proposed establishing a city near the Egyptian border where the immigrants would live until deportation.<ref>{{cite news |author=Roni Sofer |date=28 December 2010 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4005787,00.html |script-title=he:\u05d7\"\u05db \u05db\"\u05e5: \u05db\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d1\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05dc\u05d1\u05d3\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05e2\u05d5\u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=MK Katz: ball at the top of the Bedouins who help the infiltrators |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Mayor of Tel Aviv [[Ron Huldai]] demanded that the government take \"immediate emergency action.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Gilad Morag |date=4 December 2011 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4156696,00.html |script-title=he:\u05d7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05d0\u05d9 \u05dc\u05e0\u05ea\u05e0\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5: \u05ea\u05d5\u05e9\u05d1\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05e4\u05e7\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05dc \u05d4\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Huldai to Netanyahu: Residents abandoned in front of the infiltrators |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2010, a demonstration was held in Eilat against the inaction of the Israeli government. Residents claimed that they were afraid to walk outside at night in certain neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ahuva Mamus |date=11 July 2010 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3918106,00.html |script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd \u05e8\u05d5\u05e6\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d0\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d0\u05d9\u05dc\u05ea: \"\u05dc\u05d0 \u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd \u05e1\u05d5\u05d3\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd\" |language=he |trans-title=Refugees want to stay in Eilat, \"not all Sudanese\" |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> In the Shapira and Kiryat Shalom neighborhoods in southern Tel Aviv a number of real estate agents stated that they would not rent apartments to illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite news |author=Noah Koshrik |date=2 August 2010 |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/news/education/1.1214829 |script-title=he:\u05de\u05ea\u05d5\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05ea\"\u05d0: \u05dc\u05d0 \u05e0\u05e9\u05db\u05d9\u05e8 \u05d3\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05dc\u05e9\u05d1\"\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Realtors in south Tel Aviv: illegal aliens will not rent apartments |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 May 2012 a demonstration of over a thousand people was held in the [[Hatikva Quarter]]. [[Miri Regev]], [[Danny Danon]], [[Ronit Tirosh]] and [[Michael Ben-Ari]] spoke. speeches. Later on the protest turned violent.<ref>{{cite news |author=Neri Brenner |author2=Boaz Feiler |date=23 May 2012 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4233445,00.html |script-title=he:\u05de\u05d4\u05d5\u05de\u05d4 \u05d5\u05e2\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d4\u05e4\u05d2\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05ea\"\u05d0: \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05d5\u05ea\u05e7\u05e4\u05d5 |language=he |trans-title=Pandemonium and arrests at the demonstration in south Tel Aviv: Foreigners attacked |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> [[President of Israel|President]] [[Shimon Peres]] issued a condemnation of the violent words and actions against the African migrant workers, calling to refrain from racism and incitement, saying: \"Hatred of foreigners contradicts the fundamental principles of [[Judaism]]. I am well aware of the difficulties faced by the residents of south Tel Aviv [and other similar areas], but violence is not the solution.\"<ref name=no-violence>{{cite news |author=Yoni Hirsch |author2=Shlomo Cesana |author3=Yori Yalon |author4=Itsik Saban |author5=Gideon Allon |author6=Yael Branovsky |title=No place for violence against African migrants and refugees |url=http://www.israelhayom.com/site/newsletter_article.php?id=4472 |accessdate=11 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Israel HaYom]] |date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a Channel 2 interview in November 2013, Tel Aviv Mayor Ron Huldai scoffed at government policy, saying, \"Can 50,000 people be a demographic threat? That's a mockery. ... The truth is they will remain here. They are human beings and I must take care of them.\"<ref name=\"future\">{{cite news|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2013/12/22/Africans-face-uncertain-Israeli-future-after-perilous-migration.html|title=Africans face uncertain Israeli future after perilous migration|date=22 December 2013|accessdate=8 May 2014|publisher=[[Al Arabiya]]|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nRegular demonstrations and rallies supporting the refugees have also been held.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100001052021479&sk=wall |title=Ann Tifa Rave |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=11 March 2009 |url=http://wn.com/darfur_muslim_refugees_demonstrating_in_israel_to_support_icc |title=Muslim Refugees Demonstrating in Israel To Support Icc |publisher=World News Inc. |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/7708463-african-refugees-protest-in-israel |title=African Refugees Protest in Israel protests |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729054437/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/7708463-african-refugees-protest-in-israel |archivedate=29 July 2011 }}</ref> On 28 December 2013 thousands have protested in [[Tel Aviv]] against detention of asylum seekers from Sudan and Eritrea. The protesters, marched from [[Levinsky Park]] in South Tel Aviv to city center, decrying the detention without trial of African refugees in the [[Saharonim]] and [[Holot]] detention facilities. Migrants have reportedly said to fear for their life should they return to their home countries.<ref>Itay Blumenthal, [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4470485,00.html TA: Thousands protest against detention of asylum seekers], ''YNetNews'', 28 December 2013, Retrieved 29 December 2013</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2014, the Knesset Committee on Foreign Workers met to discuss the Immigration and Border Authority policy and its impact on the business sector. African migrants were present and participated in the Knesset meeting. They were supported by MK [[Michal Rozin]] of [[Meretz]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrants-take-part-in-knesset-meeting/ |title=Week after ban, African migrants take part in Knesset meeting |author=Lazar Berman |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, activists organized a [[Passover seder]] with asylum seekers at the Holot facility to recall the [[Passover]] story and call attention to the plight of the migrants. Similar seders were held in support of the migrants in Tel Aviv and Washington.<ref name=\"seder\"/> Similar events took place in 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/iw/originals/2016/04/holot-refugees-detention-freedom-passover-seder-eritrea.html#|title=\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05e9\u05db\u05dc\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05f4\u05d7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea\u05f4 \u05de\u05d7\u05db\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d7\u05d2 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05e9\u05dc\u05d4\u05dd|last=\u05e4\u05d5\u05dc\u05e1|first=\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc|website=|access-date=|date=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== International response ==\nThe Maryland-based refugee rights organization [[HIAS]], whose Israeli branch has been actively assisting African asylum seekers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hias.org/hias-israel|title=HIAS in Israel|work=HIAS|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> has vocally opposed the Israeli government's policy toward the asylum seekers and has called on Israel to evaluate their refugee status claims in accordance with international law.<ref name=\"HIAS\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hias.org/hias-calls-protection-refugees-and-asylum-seekers-israel|title=HIAS Calls for Protection of Refugees and Asylum Seekers in Israel|work=HIAS|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> The Los Angeles-based organization [[StandWithUs]], whose mission is \"supporting Israel around the world \u2013 through education and fighting anti-Semitism\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standwithus.com/aboutus/|title=StandWithUs About Us|last=HagaiZamir.com|website=www.standwithus.com|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> states that \"most of the migrants came to Israel seeking work opportunities, not as refugees escaping war\"; as StandWithUs elaborates, \"unlike refugees who are fleeing war or persecution, economic migrants leave their countries in search of better work opportunities.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swuconnect.com/insys/npoflow.v.2/_assets/pdfs/fact_sheets/African%20Migrants%20in%20Israel%20factsheet.pdf|title=African Migrants in Israel \u2013 Factsheet}}</ref> However, globally, national authorities have found asylum seekers from Eritrea deserving of refugee status in 84% of applications, and have granted refugee status to Sudanese asylum seekers 56% of the time, whereas Israel has only granted 1% of asylum petitions from these asylum seekers.<ref name=\"HIAS\"/> Mandatory lifetime conscription is among the human-rights abuses in Eritrea from which they may be fleeing.<ref name=\"truah.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.truah.org/campaign/asylum-seekers-in-israel/|title=Asylum Seekers in Israel {{!}} T'ruah|website=www.truah.org|language=English|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> The [[Rabbinical Assembly]], the clergy organization of Conservative Judaism, passed a resolution in 2016 stating that \"Israel\u2019s Ministry of the Interior has been very reluctant to grant refugee status to bona fide asylum seekers\" and calling on Israel to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rabbinicalassembly.org/story/resolution-african-asylum-seekers-israel|title=Resolution on African Asylum Seekers in Israel {{!}} The Rabbinical Assembly|website=www.rabbinicalassembly.org|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> The rabbinic human-rights organization [[T'ruah|T\u2019ruah]], based in New York, has made it a priority to encourage Israel to evaluate all asylum seekers' claims fairly.<ref name=\"truah.org\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Demographics of Israel]]\n* [[Geography of Israel]]\n* [[Illegal immigration]]\n* [[Refugee kidnappings in Sinai]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://assaf.org.il/en/ |title=ASSAF, Aid Organization for Refugees and Asylum Seekers in Israel}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://hotline.org.il/en/migrants-en/%E2%80%8Fchildren-of-migrant-workers-in-israel/ |title=Hotline for Refugees and Migrants}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.unitaf.org/ |title=unitaf, Aid Organization for Refugees and stateless children living in Israel}}\n\n[[Category:African diaspora in Israel]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Israel]]\n[[Category:Economy of Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli law]]\n[[Category:People of African descent]]\n[[Category:2000s in Israel]]\n[[Category:2010s in Israel]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Israel]]\n[[Category:Illegal immigration to Israel| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Plitim1.jpg|thumb|African migrants demonstrating in Tel Aviv]]\n'''African immigration to Israel''' is the international movement to [[Israel]] from [[Africa]] of people that are not natives or do not possess Israeli [[citizenship]] in order to settle or reside there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/us/definition/american_english/immigration|title=immigration|publisher=Oxford University Press|website=OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=11 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/immigration| title=immigrate|publisher=Merriam-Webster, In.|website=Merriam-Webster.com|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"RCUK\">{{Cite web|title=Who's who: Definitions|url=http://www.refugeecouncil.org.uk/policy_research/the_truth_about_asylum/the_facts_about_asylum |publisher=Refugee Council|location=London, England|year=2016|access-date= 7 September 2015}}</ref> This phenomenon began in the second half of the 2000s, when a large number of people from Africa entered Israel, mainly through the [[Borders of Israel#Border with Egypt|fenced border between Israel and Egypt]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} According to the data of the [[Ministry of Interior (Israel)|Israeli Interior Ministry]], 26,635 people arrived illegally in this way by July 2010,<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data 3\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02625.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05e2\u05dc \u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d5\u05db\u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea \u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=Data on crimes made by illegal immigrants and asylum seekers and of crimes made against illegal immigrants and asylum seekers|date=11 October 2010 |page=3 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> and over 55,000 by January 2012.<ref>{{cite web |date=January 2012 |url=http://www.piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/%D7%A1%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%9D%20%D7%A9%D7%A0%D7%AA%D7%99%202011.pdf |script-title=he:\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israeli foreign data |publisher=Israeli authority of population and immigration |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> In an attempt to curb the influx,<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">Butcher, Tim. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/1504945/Sharon-presses-for-fence-across-Sinai.html Sharon presses for fence across Sinai], ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 7 December 2005.</ref> Israel constructed the [[Egypt\u2013Israel barrier]], which was completed in December 2013.<ref name=\"algemeiner.com\">[http://www.algemeiner.com/2013/12/04/245-mile-1-6-billion-shekel-security-fence-between-israel-and-sinai-completed Israel Completes 245 Mile, NIS 1.6 Billion Security Fence Along Sinai Border with Egypt] Algemeiner, 4 December 2013 2:58 PM</ref>\n\nAs of January 2018, according to the Population and Immigration Authority (PIBA) there were around 30,000+ African refugees, migrants and asylum seekers in Israel, not including children born to parents in Israel.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.il/BlobFolder/reports/foreign_workers_in_israel_summary_2017/he/foreigners_in_Israel_data_2017_1.pdf|title=\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc|date=January 2018|website=Population and Immigration Authority|language=he|access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMost African migrants are regarded to be legitimate asylum seekers by human rights organizations,<ref>{{cite web |date=8 October 2012 |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/10/28/israel-asylum-seekers-blocked-border |title=Israel: Asylum Seekers Blocked at Border |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=10 January 2012 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/new-israeli-detention-law-violates-asylum-seekers-rights-2012-01-10 |title=Israel: New detention law violates rights of asylum-seekers |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> but the Israeli government says most of them are job seeking work-migrants.<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrants-reel-as-israeli-law-cuts-into-their-salaries/ African migrants reel as Israeli law cuts into their salaries]</ref>\n\nMany of the migrants seek asylum status under the United Nations [[Convention relating to the Status of Refugees]]. Citizens of [[Eritrea]] and [[Sudan]] cannot be forcibly deported from Israel. Under international law, Eritrea citizens (who, since 2009, form the majority of the undocumented workers in Israel) cannot be deported due to the opinion of the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] (UNHCR) that Eritrea has a difficult internal situation and a forced recruitment and therefore the Eritrean immigrants are defined as a \"temporary humanitarian protection group\". Israeli authorities have stated that they could not deport Sudanese directly back to Sudan because Israel has no diplomatic ties to Sudan.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2014/09/09/make-their-lives-miserable/israels-coercion-eritrean-and-sudanese-asylum-seekers|title=Make Their Lives Miserable|date=9 September 2014|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=21 January 2018}}</ref> Accordingly, the Israeli authorities grant temporary residence through \"conditional release permits\" which must be renewed every one to four months, depending on the discretion of the individual immigration official.<ref name=\":1\" /> Various authorities in Israel estimate that 80\u201390% of the undocumented workers live primarily in two centers: more than 60% in [[Tel Aviv]] and more than 20% [[Eilat]], with a few in [[Ashdod]], [[Jerusalem]] and [[Arad, Israel|Arad]].<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data 3\" />\n\n== Legal status ==\nAccording to the government, the majority of the migrants are seeking economic opportunity.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} This is not the case among Israel's allies such as the United States, where the vast majority of Eritrean and Sudanese applicants are accepted as refugees. Once in Israel, African migrants have sought refugee status for fleeing forced, open-ended conscription in Eritrea or ethnic cleansing in the Darfur region of Sudan, but the government of Israel maintains that these areas merely have a poor human rights record, which does not automatically entitle one to asylum. To qualify, applicants must establish that they face the risk of personal harm or persecution if they return to their country. The [[Ministry of Interior (Israel)|Interior Ministry]] has failed to review the vast majority of asylum requests.<ref name=\"hope\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-african-migrants-in-israel-have-little-hope-2014jan07-story.html |title=African migrants in Israel have little hope |author=David Mac Dougall and Josef Federman |publisher=Associated Press |date=7 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nMost migrants request refugee status after arriving in Israel, in accordance with the United Nations's [[Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees]]. Israel does not review the status of the individual immigrants originating from Eritrea or Sudan, who constitute about 83% of the total people coming to Israel across the Egyptian border,<ref>{{cite web |date=April 2012 |url=http://www.piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dc%202012.pdf|script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israeli foreign data |publisher=Israel Population and Immigration Authority |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> and instead automatically grants them a [[Israeli policy for Sudanese and_Eritrean refugees|\"temporary protection group\"]] status. This status allows these people to have temporary residence right within Israel, which must be renew every 3 months; usually this also means that they would be eligible for a [[work permit]] in Israel. In the past Israel also granted an automatic \"temporary protection group\" status to all citizens of the [[Ivory Coast]] and [[South Sudan]], although since then the validity of this status has expired. Regarding the other asylum requests filed by citizens of other countries and examined individually, the Interior Ministry stated that only a fraction of them were actually eligible for refugee status.<ref>{{cite news| author=Zahava Galeon |date=12 November 2010 |url=http://www.israelhayom.co.il/site/newsletter_opinion.php?id=4936&newsletter=12.11.2010 |script-title=he:\u05de\u05e1\u05d9\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd \u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Agitators against refugees |newspaper=[[Israel HaYom]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Israeli government originally tolerated the new arrivals from Africa. It allowed their entry and many migrants found menial jobs in hotels and restaurants. But after their numbers swelled, concerns were raised.<ref name=\"hope\"/> In the second half of the 2000s, there was a significant increase in the number of undocumented workers who immigrated from Africa to Israel by crossing the Egyptian border. In 2006 about 1,000 undocumented workers were detained; in 2007 about 5,000 were detained; in 2008 about 8,700 were detained; and in 2009 about 5,000 were detained.<ref>{{cite web |date=26 May 2010 |script-title=he:\u05d4\u05d8\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d2\u05d1\u05d5\u05dc \u05de\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Treatment infiltrators from the border with Egypt |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02524.pdf |publisher=Knesset Research and Information Center |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> In the first half of 2010 the migration rate even further increased in the first seven months when over 8,000 undocumented workers were caught.<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data\">{{cite web |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02625.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05e2\u05dc \u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d5\u05db\u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea \u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=Data on crimes made by illegal immigrants and asylum seekers and of crimes made against illegal immigrants and asylum seekers|date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The total number of undocumented workers is clearly greater than these figures, because many were not apprehended.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}} The early wave of undocumented workers came mainly from Sudan, while in 2009 the majority of the immigrants were from [[Eritrea]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\nIn early May 2010, it was estimated that 24,339 undocumented workers resided in Israel, of whom the number of Sudanese and Eritrean refugees who are not deportable under [[international law]] was 18,959: 5,649 Sudanese and 13,310 Eritreans. 16,766 of them received a special visa (\u05e1 2\u05d0 5) granted to illegal immigrants who are non-deportable [[asylum seekers]]. Officially, the visa allows them only to stay in the country, but in practice the state also allows the refugees to work and avoids imposing fines on the Israeli employers who employ them. This special visa requires renewal every three months.<ref>{{cite web |date=8 June 2010 |script-title=he:\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05e0\u05d9\u05e6\u05d5\u05dc \u05dc\u05de\u05d8\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05de\u05d9\u05df \u05d5\u05e2\u05d1\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05e7\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d4\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Victims of exploitation for sexual purposes and slavery among the infiltrators and asylum seekers in Israel |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/doc.asp?doc=m02534&type=pdf |publisher=Knesset Research and Information Center |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The Israeli immigration police patrols the neighborhoods of south [[Tel Aviv]] regularly and arrests asylum seekers who do not carry a valid visa; the punishment can be one to three months in prison. \n\n141 immigrants, mostly from [[Ethiopia]], received [[refugee status]].\n\nAccording to the IDF's Operations Division in 2008, most of the countries from where the illegal immigrants came are (in descending order): [[Eritrea]], [[Sudan]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Ivory Coast]] and [[Nigeria]]. Most of the illegal immigrants (85%) were men.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |date=December 2009 |url=http://web.hevra.haifa.ac.il/~ch-strategy/images/publications/darfur_refugees.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d0\u05d5 \u05de\u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d9 \u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05d4 \u05de\u05de\u05d3\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 |language=he |trans-title=Refugees or migrant workers from African states |publisher=Research Center, National Defense College and Chaikin Chair in Geostrategy, University of Haifa |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814142203/http://web.hevra.haifa.ac.il/~ch-strategy/images/publications/darfur_refugees.pdf |archivedate=14 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMost migrants initially arrive in [[Egypt]], and then pay sums of up to two thousand dollars for [[Bedouin]] smugglers to transfer them to the border between Egypt and Israel. There have been cases of abuse against the female migrants committed by the Bedouin smugglers, including [[rape]], kidnapping for ransom, and murder. Another danger for the migrants includes the Egyptian army policy to shoot at them in order to prevent crossing the Egypt/Israel border.<ref>{{cite news |author=Liam Stack |date=13 November 2008|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2008/1113/p06s03-wome.html |title=Human Rights Watch faults Egypt's 'shoot-to-stop' policy |newspaper=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Amir Bohbot |date=2 October 2011 |url=http://news.walla.co.il/?w=/0/1865224 |script-title=he:\u05ea\u05d5\u05e4\u05e2\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d2\u05d1\u05d5\u05dc \u05d4\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05de\u05d9: \u05d4\u05e6\u05d1\u05d0 \u05d4\u05de\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d9\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d1\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=The southern border phenomenon: the Egyptian army shoots infiltrators |publisher=[[Walla!]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nTo contain the illegal entry of persons, construction of the [[Egypt\u2013Israel barrier]] commenced in 2012 and was completed in 2015. 9,570 citizens of various African countries entered Israel illegally in the first half of 2012, while only 34 did the same in the first six months of 2013, after construction of the main section of the barrier was completed.<ref>[http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/169521#.UeXqBUB15DQ New Data Shows 99% Drop in Illegal Entry], Arutz Sheva. 2 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action 99.6% Drop in the Number of Infiltrators Entering Israel Due to Government Action] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930062343/http://netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action |date=30 September 2013 }}, Israeli Prime Minister official website. 1 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4402834,00.html Israel to trade arms for migrants with African countries], Ynetnews.com. 9 July 2013</ref> After the entire fence was completed, the number of migrant crossings had dropped to 16 in 2016.<ref>[http://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Israel-completes-heightened-Egypt-border-fence-478840 ISRAEL COMPLETES HEIGHTENED EGYPT BORDER FENCE]</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs of April 2012, 59,858 illegal immigrants who were never imprisoned in detention facilities have illegally enter into Israel (in August 2010 the number of the imprisoned was 1,900).<ref>{{cite web |date=April 2012 |url=http://piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dc%202012.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israel Foreign Data |publisher=Israel Population and Immigration Authority |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> Several thousands of them did not end up staying in the country.<ref>{{cite web |date=November 2011 |url=http://piba.gov.il/PublicationAndTender/ForeignWorkersStat/Documents/nov2011.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05ea\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=Israeli Foreign Data |publisher=Israel Population and Immigration Authority |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The Israeli department of immigration does not keep continuous supervision over their place of residence but, according to estimates based on data from the Israeli police, the local authorities and the aid organizations, approximately 34,000 illegal immigrants originated from [[Eritrea]], about 15,000 originated from [[Sudan]] and 10,000 originated from other countries. The Israeli [[Administration of Border Crossings, Population and Immigration]] does not keep detailed documentation regarding their place of residence, but according to estimates from 2011, which are based on data from the Israeli police, the local authorities and the NGOs, circa 15,000\u201317,000 illegal immigrants lived in [[Tel Aviv]] (mainly in southern Tel Aviv, though the number also includes illegal immigrants living in [[Bat Yam]] and [[Bnei Brak]]) and 4,000\u20138,000 living in [[Eilat]]. While the estimates in [[Ashdod]] range from 1,500 to 2,000 illegal immigrants, in [[Jerusalem]] range from 1,000 to 8,000 illegal immigrants, and in [[Arad, Israel|Arad]] range from 400 to 600 illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |date=25 May 2011 |url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/mmm/data/pdf/m02844.pdf |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05d5\u05db\u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=Crime of infiltrators and asylum seekers and against infiltrators and asylum seekers |publisher=Knesset Research and Information Center |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> As of 2017, only 39,274 of those who entered the country remain.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Criminal activity==\nIn December 2010, Police commissioner [[Dudi Cohen]] stated that despite a decline in [[robberies]] in the general population, there was a dramatic increase in this type of crime among the illegal immigrants. According to the research department of the Israel Police and Israel's foreign immigrants' crime is characterized by predominantly sectoral internal crime, in which a gun is not reported, and illegal immigrants generally have no interest in complaining to the police.<ref name=\"Knesset Crime data\" /> Due to an increase in criminal acts and the feeling of insecurity among the residents of southern Tel Aviv, the Israeli police established a new station near the New central bus station and the Shapira neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news |author=Avi Cohen |date=18 May 2012 |url=http://www.israelhayom.co.il/site/newsletter_article.php?id=17206&hp=1&newsletter=18.05.2012 |script-title=he:\u05e4\u05d7\u05d3 \u05d1\u05e8\u05d7\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea |language=he |trans-title=Fear in the streets  |newspaper=[[Israel HaYom]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> The station includes approximately 100 police officers and is expected to accommodate about 150 police officers. According to the data of the Israeli Police, which was presented to the Knesset in March 2012, from 2007 there was a steady increase in the involvement in crime of the illegal immigrants, both due to the significant increase in their numbers and for various other reasons. In 2011, 1,200 [[criminal case]]s were opened against illegal immigrants from Africa, half of them in the Tel Aviv district. This is an increase of 54% in comparison to the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |author=Omri Efraim |date=19 March 2012 |script-title=he:\u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05d8\u05e8\u05d4: \u05e2\u05dc\u05d9\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc 23% \u05d1\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9\u05e2\u05ea \u05d4\u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Police: up 23% of crime is foreign |publisher=[[Ynet]] }} http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/1,7340,L-4204802,00.html</ref>\n\nMassive protests supporting the immigrants and their remaining in Israel have taken place<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/amphtml/world/africa/thousands-of-africans-protest-israeli-deportation-plan/2018/03/24/cda24fea-2f91-11e8-8dc9-3b51e028b845_story.html|title=Thousands of Africans protest Israeli deportation plan|website=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5130004,00.html|title=20,000 asylum seekers, supporters, protest in Tel Aviv|date=25 February 2018|work=Ynetnews|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> simultaneous with other Israelis calling for their deportation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.mida.org.il/2017/03/22/south-tel-aviv-overtaken-illegal-immigrants-media-silent/|title=South Tel Aviv Being Overtaken by Illegal Immigrants, Media is Silent|date=22 March 2017|work=Mida|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5127607,00.html|title=Masses expected to attend Tel Aviv migrant solidarity rally|date=23 February 2018|work=Ynetnews|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Crime is a major factor for residents who call for the government to repatriate the migrants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4230650,00.html|title=3 Africans suspected of raping 15-year-old girl|date=17 May 2012|work=Ynetnews|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Examples include the murder of 68-year-old Esther Galili<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.maariv.co.il/news/law/Article-588893|title=\u05ea\u05d5\u05e9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05ea\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05d9\u05d1 \u05de\u05d0\u05e9\u05d9\u05de\u05d4 \u05d0\u05ea \u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05d8\u05e8\u05d4: \"\u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05e4\u05e9\u05e8 \u05dc\u05de\u05e0\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d0\u05ea \u05e8\u05e6\u05d7 \u05d0\u05de\u05d9\"|access-date=24 March 2018|language=he-IL}}</ref> who was beaten to death near her South Tel Aviv home in 2010 by a drunken Sudanese migrant. Her daughter Corine Galili is now an activist with the Residents of Southern Tel Aviv council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/155947|title=Murders by Illegals go Unreported|website=Israel National News|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Another example includes the rape of 83-year-old Ester Nahman by a 17-year-old Eritrean migrant in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://m.jpost.com/National-News/Charge-Eritrean-raped-and-beat-83-yr-old-for-hours|title=Charge: Eritrean raped and beat 83-yr-old for hours|work=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/170004|title=Eritrean Immigrant Held on Rape, Robbery of Disabled TA Woman|website=Israel National News|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> There has also been a concern of crimes committed by migrants against migrants including rape and murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrant-murdered-in-south-tel-aviv/amp/|title=African migrant murdered in south Tel Aviv {{!}} The Times of Israel|website=www.timesofisrael.com|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sudanese-woman-found-dead-in-south-tel-aviv/|title=Sudanese minor found dead in south Tel Aviv|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> According to David Filo, the police commander in charge of the district that includes south Tel Aviv, the local police station went from only four or five officers before the wave of immigrants, to more than 200 as of 2017 on duty around the clock due to the increase in crime. He stated that statistics indicate most of the crimes reported are between immigrants and include theft, drug sales and domestic violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.makorrishon.co.il/nrg/online/1/ART2/896/830.html|title=\u05de\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8 \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05df, ''\u05d0\u05dd \u05de\u05d9\u05e9\u05d4\u05d5 \u05de\u05e4\u05d7\u05d3 \u05dc\u05e6\u05d0\u05ea, \u05d9\u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05db\u05d5\u05d7 \u05e9\u05d9\u05d9\u05d2\u05e9 \u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d5''|work=NRG|access-date=24 March 2018|language=he}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli police reported experiencing difficulties dealing with criminal cases involving illegal African immigrants due to the lack of interpreters proficient in the [[Tigrinya language]] spoken in [[Eritrea]]. The Israeli legal system has encountered a similar problems.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 March 2012 |url=http://www.news1.co.il/uploadFiles/433315455913544.doc |script-title=he:\u05de\u05d3\u05d9\u05e0\u05ea \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc \u05e0\u05d2\u05d3 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d9\u05e0\u05d4 \u05e1\u05de\u05e8\u05d4\u05e8\u05d8 |language=he |trans-title=State of Israel v. Byena Smarhart |publisher=[[Supreme Court of Israel]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn her ruling on the [[Holot]] \"open detention facility\", Israeli Supreme Court justice [[Edna Arbel]] stated that whereas studies that show the level of crime committed by infiltrators is lower than in society in general, the distress of residents of South Tel Aviv should not be underestimated.<ref>{{cite web |date=16 September 2013 |last1=Arbel|first1=Edna|title=Adam v. The Knesset|url=http://elyon1.court.gov.il/files_eng/12/460/071/b24/12071460.b24.pdf |publisher=[[Supreme Court of Israel]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Handling of asylum seekers==\n[[File:Holot detention center.jpg|thumb|The entrance to Holot immigration detention center, Negev desert, Israel.]]\nIn 2010, Israel began building a [[Israel\u2013Egypt barrier|barrier]] along sections of its border with Egypt to curb the influx of [[refugees]] from African countries. Construction was completed in January 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel completes bulk of Egypt border fence |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/02/us-israel-egypt-fence-idUSBRE9010EI20130102 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2 January 2013 |accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref> 230&nbsp;km of fence have been built.<ref>{{cite news |author=Herb Keinon |url=http://www.jpost.com/Defense/PM-tours-South-heralds-completion-of-border-fence |title=PM tours South, heralds completion of border fence |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=2 January 2013 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> While 9,570 citizens of various African countries entered Israel illegally in the first half of 2012, only 34 did the same in the first six months of 2013, after construction of the barrier was completed. It represents a decrease of over 99%.<ref>{{cite news |author=Maayana Miskin |date=2 July 2013 |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/169521 |title=New Data Shows 99% Drop in Illegal Entry |publisher=[[Arutz Sheva]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action |title=99.6% Drop in the Number of Infiltrators Entering Israel Due to Government Action |publisher=Benjamin Netanyahu Official Website |date=1 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930062343/http://netanyahu.org.il/en/news/573-99-6-drop-in-the-number-of-infiltrators-entering-israel-due-to-government-action |archivedate=30 September 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIsrael also began deporting thousands of illegal immigrants residing in the country.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=3 June 2013 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/03/israel-plan-migrants-deport-east-africa |title=Israel planning to deport African migrants to 'east African country' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/middleeast/la-fg-israel-refugees-20130716,0,3081312.story |title=Israel begins deporting Eritrean refugees to troubled African homeland |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=15 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130717050104/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/middleeast/la-fg-israel-refugees-20130716%2C0%2C3081312.story |archivedate=17 July 2013  }}</ref> In 2017 Israel announced its intent to deport thousands of illegal immigrants by March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/israel-tells-african-migrants-asylum-seekers-to-leave-or-go-to-jail_us_5a4fc2c6e4b003133ec79e39|title=Israel Tells African Migrants, Asylum-Seekers To Leave Or Go To Jail|last=Cook|first=Jesselyn|date=5 January 2018|work=Huffington Post|access-date=14 January 2018|language=English}}</ref> African migrants are told to choose between returning to their home countries or being sent to third world countries, that are rumored to be Rwanda and Uganda.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/01/05/world/africa/ap-af-africa-israel-migrants.html|title=Rwanda, Uganda Deny Deal With Israel to Take Africa Migrants|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 January 2018|language=English|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Israeli Knesset announced that illegal immigrants who do not leave by March 2018 will be jailed until they leave Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://972mag.com/the-new-choice-for-asylum-seekers-deportation-or-prison/131534/|title=The new 'choice' for asylum seekers: Deportation or prison {{!}} +972 Magazine|website=972mag.com|language=English|date=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the [[Knesset]] passed an \"anti-infiltration law.\"  Advocates like MK [[Michal Rozin]] visited Saharonim and said that migrants received adequate food and medical care and were not mistreated, but said that sending migrants there was inhumane. However, conditions for many refugees elsewhere in the region are worse.<ref name=\"prison\">{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/israeli-detention-center-africans-prison |title=Israeli: Detention center for Africans a 'prison' |author=Diaa Hadid |publisher=Associated Press |date=14 July 2013 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref> After the [[Supreme Court of Israel]] declared that the long-term custody of migrants in Sahronim was unconstitutional, the government opened [[Holot]], an open detention center, in December 2013. The 1,800 residents at [[Holot]] are allowed to leave but are required to sign in once a day and return for an evening curfew.<ref name=\"hope\"/><ref name=\"seder\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrants-in-israel-hold-passover-seder/ |title=African migrants in Israel hold Passover seder |author=Tia Goldenberg |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=11 April 2014 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref> Israeli courts temporarily cancelled the summonses of African migrants to the Holot facility, and froze others until appeals can be heard against them. Judges also criticized the summons process, saying there exist fundamental problems, including the failure to examine individual circumstances and the lack of hearings for illegal immigrants. The government stated that hearings were not necessary because ordering the migrants to travel to Holot does not violate their human rights.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.575211 |title=Judges nix summonses of illegal immigrants, slam Israel's detention policy |author=Ilan Lior |newspaper=Haaretz |date=20 February 2014 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2014, the High Court struck down the anti-infiltration law (under which the [[Holot]] facility operated) and ordered the state to close [[Holot]] within 90 days.<ref name=Holot1>{{cite news | author = Ilan Lior | title = High Court orders closure of detention facility for African asylum seekers | newspaper = [[Haaretz]] | date = 22 September 2014 | url = http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.617143}}</ref> The court addressed two measures: (1) whether to limit the detention of migrants, and (2) whether to close Holot. On both measures, the court sided with the petitioners (the [[Association for Civil Rights in Israel]], the [[Hotline for Refugees and Migrants]], ASSAF, [[Kav LaOved]], [[Physicians for Human Rights\u2013Israel]], and [[Amnesty International]]\u2013Israel).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/in-dramatic-ruling-supreme-court-rejects-israels-policies-on-illegal-migrants/ |title=In dramatic ruling, High Court rejects Israel's policies on illegal migrants |author=Marissa Newman |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=22 September 2014}}</ref> The ruling said that conditions at the facility were an \"unbearable violation of [their] basic rights, first and foremost the right to freedom and the right to dignity\".<ref name=Holot1/> Illegal migrants can no longer be detained for up to a year without trial, however detention continues within legal boundaries.<ref name=\"new law\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-ministers-mull-new-migrant-law/ |title=Netanyahu, ministers mull new migrant law |publisher=AFP |date=7 October 2014}}</ref> The detentions in Holot have continued, with illegal immigrants being detained for a year and then being prevented from living in Tel Aviv and Eilat upon their release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/26/middleeast/israel-migrant-release/index.html|title=Israel frees 1,200 migrants, bans them from Tel Aviv|author-link=Oren Liebermann|first=Oren |last=Liebermann|work=CNN|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> In November 2017, the Israeli government announced that it would be closing the Holot Detention Center within four months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5044929,00.html|title=Government approves closure of Holot facility within 4 months|date=19 November 2017|work=Ynetnews|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nA law passed in 2017 required that employers impose a 20 per cent deduction on the [[wages]] of workers who entered the country illegally from [[Egypt]]. The deducted money is deposited in a fund along with an employer paid [[Taxation in Israel|tax]] of 16 per cent. This money is accessible to workers only when they leave Israel.<ref>{{Cite web| title = African migrant families battle hunger in Israel| work = Middle East Monitor| accessdate = 8 November 2018| date = 8 November 2018| url = https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181108-african-migrant-families-battle-hunger-in-israel/}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Israel reached an agreement with the [[United Nations]] to expel around 16,000 African migrants to Western countries in exchange for granting temporary residency in Israel to the same number.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Israel-announces-it-reached-deal-with-UN-on-deportation-of-asylum-seekers-547703|title=Israel reaches deal with U.N. to resettle asylum seekers in Western states|work=Jerusalem Post|date=2 April 2018}}</ref> Shortly after, however, the deal was cancelled by the Israeli government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Netanyahu-completes-about-face-on-migrants-says-UNHRC-deal-is-cancelled-547777|title=Netanyahu completes about-face on migrants, says UNHCR deal is cancelled|work=Jerusalem Post|date=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aid organizations==\nIsrael has a number of organizations focused legal aid, including the [[Hotline for Refugees and Migrants]], ASSAF, [[Physicians for Human Rights-Israel]], [[African Refugees Development Center]] and [[Association for Civil Rights in Israel]].  The secular Jewish organization [[BINA Center for Jewish Identity and Hebrew Culture|Bina]], located in south Tel Aviv, has helped asylum seekers as well as Israeli citizens understand refugee rights, and has undertaken advocacy and educational activities including frequent trips for Israelis to visit the Holot Detention Center. Most of these organization are funded by the [[New Israel Fund]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Akiva Bigman |date=1 January 2014 |url=http://mida.org.il/2014/01/01/%D7%90%D7%A1%D7%98%D7%A8%D7%98%D7%92%D7%99%D7%99%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%93%D7%A2%D7%95%D7%95%D7%94-%D7%A9%D7%9C-%D7%94%D7%A7%D7%A8%D7%9F-%D7%94%D7%97%D7%93%D7%A9%D7%94-%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%A8%D7%90/ |script-title=he:\u05d0\u05e1\u05d8\u05e8\u05d8\u05d2\u05d9\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4'\u05d3\u05e2\u05d5\u05d5\u05d4' \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05d4\u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc |language=he |trans-title=The strategy 'Dawa' of the New Israel Fund |publisher=MIDA |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> Relief organizations have been involved in discussions held in Knesset committees on this issue and have submitted a petition against the measures the state has taken to put a halt to the phenomenon of immigration.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\nunitaf creates early-childhood programs for refugee and stateless children living in Israel <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/.premium-who-will-save-the-refugee-children-of-tel-aviv-1.5347117/|title=Who Will Save the Refugee Children of Tel Aviv?|date=5 April 2015|publisher=Haaretz}}</ref>; the President of the board is [[Aliza Olmert]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unitaf.org/a-word-from-aliza-olmert/|title=President of the Board at unitaf - unitaf|date=8 April 2020|publisher=unitaf.org}}</ref>\n\n==Response in Israel==\nIsrael was founded in the wake of the Holocaust and has provided refuge to Jews fleeing oppression around the world. On one hand, many Israelis feel Israel has a special responsibility to assist refugees in such dire conditions.<ref name=\"hope\"/><ref name=\"seder\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sabar|first=Galia|last2=Tsurkov|first2=Elizabeth|date=May 2015|title=Israel's Policies towards Asylum-Seekers:2012\u20132014|journal=Instituto Affari Internazionali|volume=20|pages=2\u201318|isbn=978-88-98650-44-6}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli reaction to African migrants has been mixed. In 2010, Israelis protested the construction of the Holot detention facility built to detain illegal immigrants, stating that its construction goes against Human Rights values. At the same time, residents of South Tel Aviv demonstrated against the presence of foreigners living in their communities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/thousands-in-tel-aviv-protest-plan-for-refugee-detention-facility-1.332737|title=Thousands in Tel Aviv Protest Plan for Refugee Detention Facility|last=Lior|first=Ilan|date=24 December 2010|work=Haaretz|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> In 2012, nearly 1,000 Israelis, mostly from neighborhoods in South Tel Aviv staged a protest against illegal immigrants, joined by Member of Knesset[[Miri Regev]], they asked the government for deportation and expulsion of migrants from Africa.  Regev stated  \"the Sudanese were a cancer in our body.\" This protest led to destruction of property and businesses owned by Sudanese and Eritrean people as well as violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/06/10/israel-amend-anti-infiltration-law|title=Israel: Amend 'Anti-Infiltration' Law|date=10 June 2012|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/demonstrators-attack-african-migrants-in-south-tel-aviv-1.432262|title=Demonstrators Attack African Migrants in South Tel Aviv|last=Lior|first=Ilan|date=24 May 2012|work=Haaretz|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> In 2015, an immigrant from Eritrea, Habtom Zarhum, was beaten to death by a mob after being misidentified as the perpetrator in a [[Beersheva bus station shooting|terrorist attack at the Beersheva bus station]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/1.681069|title=Two Dead, 11 Wounded in Shooting Attack in Southern Israel|last=Ben Zikri|first=Almog|date=19 October 2015|website=Haaretz|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany Israelis have continued to show their support over the years for the community. Refugee [[Passover Seder|Seders]] have been held each year during the Jewish holiday of [[Passover]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Activists-hold-Seder-for-African-asylum-seekers-at-Holot-facility-451436|title=CTIVISTS HOLD SEDER FOR AFRICAN ASYLUM-SEEKERS AT HOLOT FACILITY|last=Sharon|first=Jeremy|date=17 April 2016|work=Jerusalem Post|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> Support is also demonstrated through the work of non-profit organizations, including [http://www.kavlaoved.org.il/en/ Kav LaOved (Worker's Hotline]), [https://www.ardc-israel.org/ ARDC], [http://assaf.org.il/en/node/2 ASSAF]. In late 2017, early 2018, North American Jewish organizations joined with Israeli NGOs to decry Israel's decision to close Holot and deport asylum seekers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/North-American-Jewish-leaders-Please-dont-deport-Africans-533195|title=NORTH AMERICAN JEWISH LEADERS: PLEASE DON'T DEPORT AFRICANS|last=Eisenbud|first=Daniel|date=9 January 2018|work=Jerusalem Post|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli demographer [[Arnon Soffer]] claims that from a security perspective, the migrants may serve as informant or as operatives of terrorist organizations. Socially, he claims that they are contributing to congestion in the cities and a rise in [[crime]]. From the demographic perspective, he perceives them as a [[Demographic threat#Israel|demographic threat]] to the Jewish majority. According to Sofer, failing to stop the illegal immigration waves at an early stage will only lead to much larger waves in the future.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nIsraeli economic commentator [[Nehemiah Shtrasler]] estimated that illegal immigrants take the places of weaker manual workers, causing loss of jobs and a reduction in the wages. He also claimed that they burden the health care, welfare and education systems. \"We would never be able to raise the standard of living of the needy and reduce the gaps, if we keep on absorbing more and more destitute people.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=24 September 2010 |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/opinions/1.1222412 |script-title=he:\u05e0\u05d7\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d8\u05e8\u05e1\u05dc\u05e8 &#124; 40 \u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05d5\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Nehemiah Shtrasler &#124; 4- Infiltrators a day |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli MK [[Ya'akov Katz (politician born 1951)|Ya'akov Katz]], who headed the government committee on issue of illegal asylum seekers, proposed establishing a city near the Egyptian border where the immigrants would live until deportation.<ref>{{cite news |author=Roni Sofer |date=28 December 2010 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4005787,00.html |script-title=he:\u05d7\"\u05db \u05db\"\u05e5: \u05db\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d1\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05dc\u05d1\u05d3\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05e2\u05d5\u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=MK Katz: ball at the top of the Bedouins who help the infiltrators |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Mayor of Tel Aviv [[Ron Huldai]] demanded that the government take \"immediate emergency action.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Gilad Morag |date=4 December 2011 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4156696,00.html |script-title=he:\u05d7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05d0\u05d9 \u05dc\u05e0\u05ea\u05e0\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5: \u05ea\u05d5\u05e9\u05d1\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05e4\u05e7\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05dc \u05d4\u05de\u05e1\u05ea\u05e0\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Huldai to Netanyahu: Residents abandoned in front of the infiltrators |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2010, a demonstration was held in Eilat against the inaction of the Israeli government. Residents claimed that they were afraid to walk outside at night in certain neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ahuva Mamus |date=11 July 2010 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3918106,00.html |script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd \u05e8\u05d5\u05e6\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d0\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d0\u05d9\u05dc\u05ea: \"\u05dc\u05d0 \u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd \u05e1\u05d5\u05d3\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd\" |language=he |trans-title=Refugees want to stay in Eilat, \"not all Sudanese\" |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> In the Shapira and Kiryat Shalom neighborhoods in southern Tel Aviv a number of real estate agents stated that they would not rent apartments to illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite news |author=Noah Koshrik |date=2 August 2010 |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/news/education/1.1214829 |script-title=he:\u05de\u05ea\u05d5\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05ea\"\u05d0: \u05dc\u05d0 \u05e0\u05e9\u05db\u05d9\u05e8 \u05d3\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05dc\u05e9\u05d1\"\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd |language=he |trans-title=Realtors in south Tel Aviv: illegal aliens will not rent apartments |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 May 2012 a demonstration of over a thousand people was held in the [[Hatikva Quarter]]. [[Miri Regev]], [[Danny Danon]], [[Ronit Tirosh]] and [[Michael Ben-Ari]] spoke. speeches. Later on the protest turned violent.<ref>{{cite news |author=Neri Brenner |author2=Boaz Feiler |date=23 May 2012 |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4233445,00.html |script-title=he:\u05de\u05d4\u05d5\u05de\u05d4 \u05d5\u05e2\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d4\u05e4\u05d2\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d1\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05ea\"\u05d0: \u05d6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05d5\u05ea\u05e7\u05e4\u05d5 |language=he |trans-title=Pandemonium and arrests at the demonstration in south Tel Aviv: Foreigners attacked |publisher=[[Ynet]] |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> [[President of Israel|President]] [[Shimon Peres]] issued a condemnation of the violent words and actions against the African migrant workers, calling to refrain from racism and incitement, saying: \"Hatred of foreigners contradicts the fundamental principles of [[Judaism]]. I am well aware of the difficulties faced by the residents of south Tel Aviv [and other similar areas], but violence is not the solution.\"<ref name=no-violence>{{cite news |author=Yoni Hirsch |author2=Shlomo Cesana |author3=Yori Yalon |author4=Itsik Saban |author5=Gideon Allon |author6=Yael Branovsky |title=No place for violence against African migrants and refugees |url=http://www.israelhayom.com/site/newsletter_article.php?id=4472 |accessdate=11 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Israel HaYom]] |date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a Channel 2 interview in November 2013, Tel Aviv Mayor Ron Huldai scoffed at government policy, saying, \"Can 50,000 people be a demographic threat? That's a mockery. ... The truth is they will remain here. They are human beings and I must take care of them.\"<ref name=\"future\">{{cite news|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/features/2013/12/22/Africans-face-uncertain-Israeli-future-after-perilous-migration.html|title=Africans face uncertain Israeli future after perilous migration|date=22 December 2013|accessdate=8 May 2014|publisher=[[Al Arabiya]]|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nRegular demonstrations and rallies supporting the refugees have also been held.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=100001052021479&sk=wall |title=Ann Tifa Rave |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=11 March 2009 |url=http://wn.com/darfur_muslim_refugees_demonstrating_in_israel_to_support_icc |title=Muslim Refugees Demonstrating in Israel To Support Icc |publisher=World News Inc. |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/7708463-african-refugees-protest-in-israel |title=African Refugees Protest in Israel protests |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729054437/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/7708463-african-refugees-protest-in-israel |archivedate=29 July 2011 }}</ref> On 28 December 2013 thousands have protested in [[Tel Aviv]] against detention of asylum seekers from Sudan and Eritrea. The protesters, marched from [[Levinsky Park]] in South Tel Aviv to city center, decrying the detention without trial of African refugees in the [[Saharonim]] and [[Holot]] detention facilities. Migrants have reportedly said to fear for their life should they return to their home countries.<ref>Itay Blumenthal, [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4470485,00.html TA: Thousands protest against detention of asylum seekers], ''YNetNews'', 28 December 2013, Retrieved 29 December 2013</ref>\n\nOn 15 January 2014, the Knesset Committee on Foreign Workers met to discuss the Immigration and Border Authority policy and its impact on the business sector. African migrants were present and participated in the Knesset meeting. They were supported by MK [[Michal Rozin]] of [[Meretz]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/african-migrants-take-part-in-knesset-meeting/ |title=Week after ban, African migrants take part in Knesset meeting |author=Lazar Berman |newspaper=The Times of Israel |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, activists organized a [[Passover seder]] with asylum seekers at the Holot facility to recall the [[Passover]] story and call attention to the plight of the migrants. Similar seders were held in support of the migrants in Tel Aviv and Washington.<ref name=\"seder\"/> Similar events took place in 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/iw/originals/2016/04/holot-refugees-detention-freedom-passover-seder-eritrea.html#|title=\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05d8 \u05e9\u05db\u05dc\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05f4\u05d7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea\u05f4 \u05de\u05d7\u05db\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d7\u05d2 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05e9\u05dc\u05d4\u05dd|last=\u05e4\u05d5\u05dc\u05e1|first=\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc|website=|access-date=|date=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== International response ==\nThe Maryland-based refugee rights organization [[HIAS]], whose Israeli branch has been actively assisting African asylum seekers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hias.org/hias-israel|title=HIAS in Israel|work=HIAS|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> has vocally opposed the Israeli government's policy toward the asylum seekers and has called on Israel to evaluate their refugee status claims in accordance with international law.<ref name=\"HIAS\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hias.org/hias-calls-protection-refugees-and-asylum-seekers-israel|title=HIAS Calls for Protection of Refugees and Asylum Seekers in Israel|work=HIAS|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> The Los Angeles-based organization [[StandWithUs]], whose mission is \"supporting Israel around the world \u2013 through education and fighting anti-Semitism\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standwithus.com/aboutus/|title=StandWithUs About Us|last=HagaiZamir.com|website=www.standwithus.com|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> states that \"most of the migrants came to Israel seeking work opportunities, not as refugees escaping war\"; as StandWithUs elaborates, \"unlike refugees who are fleeing war or persecution, economic migrants leave their countries in search of better work opportunities.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swuconnect.com/insys/npoflow.v.2/_assets/pdfs/fact_sheets/African%20Migrants%20in%20Israel%20factsheet.pdf|title=African Migrants in Israel \u2013 Factsheet}}</ref> However, globally, national authorities have found asylum seekers from Eritrea deserving of refugee status in 84% of applications, and have granted refugee status to Sudanese asylum seekers 56% of the time, whereas Israel has only granted 1% of asylum petitions from these asylum seekers.<ref name=\"HIAS\"/> Mandatory lifetime conscription is among the human-rights abuses in Eritrea from which they may be fleeing.<ref name=\"truah.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.truah.org/campaign/asylum-seekers-in-israel/|title=Asylum Seekers in Israel {{!}} T'ruah|website=www.truah.org|language=English|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> The [[Rabbinical Assembly]], the clergy organization of Conservative Judaism, passed a resolution in 2016 stating that \"Israel\u2019s Ministry of the Interior has been very reluctant to grant refugee status to bona fide asylum seekers\" and calling on Israel to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rabbinicalassembly.org/story/resolution-african-asylum-seekers-israel|title=Resolution on African Asylum Seekers in Israel {{!}} The Rabbinical Assembly|website=www.rabbinicalassembly.org|access-date=14 January 2018}}</ref> The rabbinic human-rights organization [[T'ruah|T\u2019ruah]], based in New York, has made it a priority to encourage Israel to evaluate all asylum seekers' claims fairly.<ref name=\"truah.org\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Demographics of Israel]]\n* [[Geography of Israel]]\n* [[Illegal immigration]]\n* [[Refugee kidnappings in Sinai]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://assaf.org.il/en/ |title=ASSAF, Aid Organization for Refugees and Asylum Seekers in Israel}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://hotline.org.il/en/migrants-en/%E2%80%8Fchildren-of-migrant-workers-in-israel/ |title=Hotline for Refugees and Migrants}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.unitaf.org/ |title=unitaf, Aid Organization for Refugees and stateless children living in Israel}}\n\n[[Category:African diaspora in Israel]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Israel]]\n[[Category:Economy of Israel]]\n[[Category:Israeli law]]\n[[Category:People of African descent]]\n[[Category:2000s in Israel]]\n[[Category:2010s in Israel]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Israel]]\n[[Category:Illegal immigration to Israel| ]]\n", "name_user": "109.66.86.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_immigration_to_Israel"}
{"title_page": "Benee", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{short description|New Zealand singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Benee\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Benee performing live at Spotify's Front Left Live playlist event in Melbourne (2019) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Benee at [[Forum Theatre|The Forum]] in October 2019\n| birth_name       = Stella Rose Bennett<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opencorporates.com/officers/374086399|title=Stella Rose BENNETT: Director of BeneMusicc LTD (New Zealand)|website=[[OpenCorporates]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315092944/https://opencorporates.com/officers/374086399|archive-date=15 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Grey Lynn]], [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/benee-mn0003850385/biography|title=BENEE: Biography & History|last=Donelson|first=Marcy|website=[[AllMusic]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|2000|1|30|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B78QiiXgACD/?igshid=1dpjqnrlrqdib|title=@beneemusic on Instagram: 20 \ud83e\udd0e|publisher=BENEE [verified account]|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|website=Instagram}}</ref>\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| label            = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| website          = {{url|beneemusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Stella Rose Bennett''' (born 30 January 2000), known professionally as '''Benee''' ({{IPAc-en|'|b|\u025b|n|i\u02d0}}, stylised '''BENEE''', formerly spelt '''Bene''') is a [[New Zealand]] singer and songwriter from [[Auckland]]. In 2019, Benee won 4 [[New Zealand Music Awards]], namely [[New Zealand Music Award for Single of the Year|Single of The Year]], [[New Zealand Music Award for Best Solo Artist|Best Solo Artist]], [[New Zealand Music Award for Breakthrough Artist of the Year|Best Breakthrough Artist]] and Best Pop Artist. She is best known for her singles \"[[Glitter (Benee song)|Glitter]]\", \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\" and \"[[Supalonely]]\" which have gained over 164 million [[Streaming media|streams]] on [[Spotify]] altogether.<!-- Use Spotify's desktop app to see stats on Benee's artist page --> Since 2018, Benee has earned 4 credits on the [[Triple J Hottest 100]], 3 of which were in [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2019|the 2019 list]].\n\nBenee made her solo debut under the moniker of Bene with the 2017 single \"Tough Guy\", before gaining prominence with her 2018 single \"Soaked\", which was certified double-platinum in New Zealand. She released her debut EP, ''[[Fire on Marzz]]'', with help from producer [[Kidz in Space|Josh Fountain]] in June 2019. Her second EP, ''[[Stella & Steve]]'', was released in November 2019 and charted in the US, Canada and France as a result of the international success of the EP's final single \"Supalonely\".\n\n== Life and career ==\n\n=== 2000\u20132016: Early life ===\nStella Rose Bennett was born and raised in the suburb of [[Grey Lynn]] in [[Auckland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fashionjournal.com.au/music/get-to-know-benee/|title=Get to know Benee, if you know what's good for you|last=Sholly|first=Eliza|date=29 November 2019|website=Fashion Journal|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spinoff\">{{cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/13-07-2019/it-was-a-bit-nuts-kind-of-mindblowing-benee-on-touring-the-world-and-stuffing-up/ |title=\u2018It was a bit nuts, mindblowing\u2019: Benee on touring the world and stuffing up |last=McAuley |first=Matthew |publisher=[[The Spinoff]]|date=14 July 2019|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref> She grew up in a \"really musical\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.neckofthewoods.co.nz/word-in-the-woods/2018/7/31/revealing-bene|title=Revealing BENE|date=31 July 2018|website=Neck of The Woods|language=en-NZ|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> family with parents who would expose her to the catalogs of [[Radiohead]], [[Bj\u00f6rk]] and [[Groove Armada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/nat-music/audio/2018731105/the-mixtape-benee|title=Six things you probably didn\u2019t know about Benee|date=24 January 2020|website=[[RNZ]]|language=en-nz|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/jgeg8b/benee-and-gus-dapperton-turn-breakup-blues-into-sunny-pop-on-supalonely|title=BENEE and Gus Dapperton turn breakup blues into sunny pop on Supalonely|last=Marsh|first=Ariana|date=4 February 2020|website=[[i-D]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buro247.my/culture/music/benee-interview-music-tiktok-supalonely.html|title=Benee: A melodic conversation with the 'Supalonely' singer on her music, TikTok, and more|last=Tan|first=Ronn|date=9 April 2020|website=BURO.|url-status=live|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> From the age of eight she learnt how to play the guitar as well as the saxophone, before only becoming interested in writing and recording music at the age of 17.<ref name=\":2\" /> Bennett attended a single-sex catholic school, [[St Mary's College, Auckland|St Mary's College]], where music was compulsory for four years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stmaryak.school.nz/images/Article-Attachments/Student-life/SMC-Music-Information-2020.pdf|title=St. Mary's College Music Important FAQs|website=[[St Mary's College, Auckland|St. Mary's College]]|url-status=live|access-date=3 April 2020|postscript=. '''Note:''' See ''Music Wall of Fame''}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== 2017\u20132018: Online beginnings and solo debut ===\nBenee began her music career by posting covers to [[SoundCloud]], and began making her own music in her final year of high school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/zmpwny/new-zealand-popstar-benee-|title=10 things you need to know about hazy pop superstar benee|last=Kheraj|first=Alim|date=4 June 2019|website=i-D|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> After dropping out of a communications degree at the [[Auckland University of Technology]] after two weeks, during what she called \"a quarter-life crisis\", she decided to enter the music business professionally.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12285432|title=What you need to know about Benee, NZ music's rising star|date=14 November 2019|work=[[NZ Herald]]|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> Her music caught the attention of [[Josh Fountain]], a producer and member of the band Leisure, with whom she worked with for both her 2017 debut single \"Tough Guy\" as well as her 2018 single \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2020/01/benee-interview|title=Meet BENEE, A Kiwi Pop Star in the Making|last=Yu|first=Eda|date=7 January 2020|website=[[Complex (website)|Complex]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sniffers.co.nz/article/auckland-teen-bene-makes-visual-debut-tough-guy|title=Auckland teen Bene makes her visual debut with \u2018Tough Guy\u2019|last=Tetlow|first=Max|date=28 February 2018|website=Sniffers|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Benee (as Bene) earned her first career entry on the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2018|Triple J Hottest 100 2018]] with \"Soaked\" at #58.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/18/countdown/1-100/|title=triple j Hottest 100 2018|website=[[ABC Australia]]|language=en-AU|url-status=live|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: ''Fire on Marzz'' and ''Stella & Steve'' ===\nUnder the moniker of \"Bene\", Bennett released her debut EP ''[[Fire on Marzz]]'' on 28 June 2019, before later adding an \"e\" because of \"pronunciation woes\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fenwick|first=George|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12245884|title=Album review: Benee, Fire on Marzz|date=11 July 2019|work=NZ Herald|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> and copyright issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7820282/benee-interview-2019-fire-on-marzz-ep|title=Interview: BENEE Talks Debut EP 'FIRE ON MARZZ' & BENEEvision|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=2 July 2019|website=[[idolator (website)|idolator]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The EP, which was described by [[George Fenwick]] of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' as \"a funky, sun-soaked record\", peaked at #13 on the [[New Zealand Albums Chart]] and at #75 on the [[Australian Albums Chart]]. The EP also earned Benee the award for [[New Zealand Music Award for Best Solo Artist|Best Solo Artist]] at the [[2019 New Zealand Music Awards]] in November 2019, where she also won awards for [[New Zealand Music Award for Single of the Year|Single of the Year]] with \"[[Soaked (song)|Soaked]]\", [[New Zealand Music Award for Breakthrough Artist of the Year|Best Breakthrough Artist]] and Best Pop Artist.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/117426344/kiwi-pop-sensation-benee-claims-four-titles-at-the-vodafone-new-zealand-music-awards|title=Kiwi pop sensation Benee claims four titles at the Vodafone New Zealand Music Awards|date=15 November 2019|website=Stuff NZ|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBenee's follow-up EP, ''[[Stella & Steve]]'', was released on 15 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8543343/benee-interview-stella-steve-ep|title=Benee Interview: Singer Talks 'Stella & Steve' EP|last=Ginsberg|first=Gab|date=13 November 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The EP features the single \"[[Supalonely]]\" featuring [[Gus Dapperton]], which later gained international success in March 2020 after a viral dance challenge accompanied by the song spawned on the online video-sharing platform [[TikTok]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7907879/future-hit-benees-supalonely-is-absolutely-irresistible|title=Future Hit: BENEE's \"Supalonely\" Is Absolutely Irresistible|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=10 March 2020|website=[[idolator (website)|idolator]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/videos/benees-supalonely-is-ultra-infectious|title=BENEE's 'Supalonely' Is Ultra-Infectious|last=Murray|first=Robin|date=6 March 2020|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> This became her second song to become viral on TikTok after \"[[Glitter (Benee song)|Glitter]]\" spawned a similar dance challenge in December 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://theindustryobserver.thebrag.com/benees-glitter-is-a-dance-challenge-on-tiktok/|title=Benee\u2019s \u2018Glitter\u2019 is a dance challenge on TikTok|last=Reid|first=Poppy|date=19 December 2019|website=The Industry Observer|language=en-AU|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Benee also supported American singer-songwriter [[Conan Gray]] for nine nights of his [[Comfort Crowd Tour]] of North America during December 2019.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2NZZJkpfSt/|title=Conan Gray on Instagram: \"HEY Y\u2019ALL \ud83d\udda4 so excited to announce that @whoisumi and @beneemusic are coming on my upcoming north american tour with me!! check out dates\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref> Benee's singles, \"Glitter,\" \"[[Find an Island|Find and Island]],\" and \"Evil Spider\" each appeared in the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2019|2019 Triple J Hottest 100]] at 19, 25 and 51 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/19/#/1-100|title=triple j Hottest 100 2019|website=[[ABC Australia]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn an interview for ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'', Benee revealed that she has [[dyslexia]]. She also described her childhood experiences with songwriting:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=12216330|title=Meet Bene: The Kiwi teen taking over the charts|last=Fenwick|first=George|date=2019-03-27|access-date=2019-06-20|issn=1170-0777}}</ref> <blockquote>throughout school I struggled with writing....I liked creative writing, that was what I loved, but I was always making mistakes, and I was confined to this way that I should write....Songwriting for me was this place where I don't have to be grammatically correct. Learning the craft with [Josh Fountain], when he was sharing all his knowledge \u2013 something clicked, and I was just like, I love this. It's a great emotional outlet for me; I just love splashing what I feel on to a track.</blockquote>\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br/><ref name=\"NZBenee\">{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Benee|title=Discography Benee|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]. Hung Medien|url-status=live|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" styl